<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Maintain Ban on British Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A proposal on easing the ban on
British beef export has failed to win sufficient support of the
chief veterinarians from the European Union's 15 member states.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Veterinary Committee, made up by the chief
veterinarians, Wednesday failed to reach the qualified majority on
the United Kingdom's Export Certified Herds Scheme which would
allow for a limited resumption in beef exports from Northern
Ireland alone, said an EU statement released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Franz Fischler and Emma Bonino, European commissioners
respectively responsible for agriculture and health, described the
outcome of the discussions as "most regrettable."
</P>
<P>
They indicated that the issue would be sent to the Council of
Ministers for a decision on March 16 and 17.
</P>
<P>
An EU official, who declined to be identified, said the
proposal obtained a simple majority in Wednesday's discussion, but
"the qualified majority needed wasn't reached."
</P>
<P>
But under EU voting rules, a simple majority at ministerial
level would be enough to carry the proposal through. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
