<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ceremonies Mark Centenary of Late Chinese Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Premier Zhou Enlai passed away
some 22 years ago but still remains alive deep in the hearts of
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 people visited an exhibition today at the
Museum of Chinese Revolution to mark the centenary of Zhou's birth.
</P>
<P>
More than 290,000 have visited the exhibition since it opened
on February 10. Overwhelming demand has resulted in the exhibition
being extended from the originally planned closing date of March
20 to April 30.
</P>
<P>
Speakers addressing a recent Ministry of Culture meeting
recalled Zhou's great concern for Chinese artists.
</P>
<P>
Numerous related activities have been held throughout China,
including a trade fair in Zhou's native home of Huai'an, Jiangsu
Province, as well as recognition of a new railway serving the
city, and the establishment of a sister-city relationship between
Huai'an and Yorba Linda, California. the hometown of former
U.S. President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
Zhou and Nixon have been praised for their contributions to
normalizing Sino-US diplomatic relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
