<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Vehicles Sales Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Vehicle sales in Canada slid 3.7
percent in February from year-earlier levels, reports said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Canada's sales of cars, trucks and minivans fell to 84,068 in
February from 87,285 a year ago. It's the second month in a row
that sales have declined.
</P>
<P>
One explanation for the slow start to 1998 is that aggressive
incentive plans in late 1997 took some steam out of the market,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Though the auto industry is expecting the total market to be up
at least four percent in 1998, growth will be far below 1997's
18.3 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
In February, Chrysler Canada Ltd. was the only member of the
Big Three to report a big growth of 14.9 percent, while Ford of
Canada Ltd. and General Motors of Canada Ltd. saw a 19.7 percent
and 13.5 percent drop respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Europe-and Asia-based manufacturers got big
gains, ranging from Toyota Canada Inc.'s 31.8 percent growth to
BMW's 42.6 percent increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
