<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Trade Union Leaders on National Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) Thursday described the two-day nationwide stayaway
by workers as a ''well deserved victory''.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the workers in most of the urban centres
stayed at home on Tuesday and Wednesday in response to a ACTU
call to protest rising prices of basic commodities and unpopular
government taxes.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here Thursday afternoon, ZCTU
Secretary-General Morgan Tsvangirai said the ZCTU could not just
sit and ignore the problems facing the nation, and urged the
government to be sensitive to the demands of the masses.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to threats from the government that civil servants
who observed the stayaway would be punished, Tsvangirai said the
ZCTU had already put in place legal systems to defend those
affected.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued after the news conference, ZCTU
President Gibson Sibanda said the two-day mass stay-away was
characterised by high levels of discipline of purpose.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''The workers have finally realised that they need to
work nationally to counteract the effects of price increases and
higher taxes.''
</P>
<P>
''No amount of threats, intimidation and provocation will
drive a wedge between genuine workers' demands and their
authentic leadership,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
Tsvangirai stressed, ''Like before, we genuinely seek solution
to pressing economic issues through participation in economic
decision making. We will work with our social partners in
developing a lasting national consensus.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
