<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Cabinet Approves Economic Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean cabinet has
approved a police framework for the indigenization of the economy
to enable the economically marginalized black majority to enter
the mainstream economy, a senior Zimbabwean official said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for State Enterprises and Indigenization
Cephas Msipa said at a news conference here that the policy would
ensure the development of private sector which would be the
engine of economic growth and development as well as correcting
past imbalances.
</P>
<P>
The main objective of the policy was to economically empower
indigenous Zimbabweans by increasing, through economic expansion,
their productive investment in the economy to create more wealth
and eradicate poverty, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives were to create conditions that allow
disadvantaged people to participate in the economic development
and "earn themselves self respect and dignity" while developing a
self-sustaining economic structure.
</P>
<P>
He said that the potential for inter-racial conflict would
"persist in Zimbabwe as long as economic justice is not
attained."
</P>
<P>
"In this regard, the underlying philosophy to indigenization
is to improve the lives of the indigenous majority," he said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the success of the program, he said, the government
would work towards creating an enabling macro-economic
environment, redistributing the land, the mobilization of
financial resources and reviewing laws that constrain
indigenization and industrialization of the economy.
</P>
<P>
Measures to economically empower people would be implemented
through privatizing state enterprises, practising employee share
ownership schemes, joint ventures and strategic partnerships, the
operationalization of national investment trust, sub-contracting
and business linkages, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that at the moment 80 percent of the
country'seconomy is dominated by large foreign and local
multi-nationals and the minority white. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
