<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communist Party of Nepal Split </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), the largest party in the
parliament, formally broke up Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bam Dev Gautam, former deputy prime minister and leader of a
minority faction of the CPN-UML, and the party's 40 MPs registered
a new party Thursday afternoon in the Parliament Secretariat,
General Secretary of the CPN-UML Madhav Kumar Nepal confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Under Nepal's law, 40 percent of members of a parliamentary
party or its central committee can form a new party and get
recognition. The CPN-UML has 89 MPs in the parliament, so the
breakaway faction has got more than what is needed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Committee of the CPN-UML at a meeting in
the morning expelled Gautam and his supporters from the party.
</P>
<P>
Differences between Gautam and General Secretary Nepal led to
the split of the party.
</P>
<P>
At the party's Sixth National Congress held in late January,
Kumar Nepal's political documents were adopted while Gautam and
his supporters boycotted the election of the central committee.
</P>
<P>
Several rounds of negotiations held since then failed to patch
up the differences.
</P>
<P>
The breakup followed a split of the country's third largest
party the ruling National Democratic Party in January, when former
Prime Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand and his supporters left the
party to form a new organization. Their new party has won formal
recognition in the parliament, but the Election Commission has not
recognized it as a national party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Edge 0.5 Pct in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. orders to factories
and mines edged 0.5 percent in January, the Commerce Department
reported here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The January growth followed a revised 2.6 percent drop in
December, which had been the worst showing for the U.S.
manufacturers in more than five years, according to the
department.
</P>
<P>
The steep drop in December was attributed mainly a falloff in
demand for aircraft. Aircraft orders rebounded sharply in January,
rising 71.9 percent and helping to push the overall transportation
category up by 5.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, demand for U.S. manufactured goods was extremely weak,
dropping by 0.2 percent, the third setback in the last four
months.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that a recent financial crisis in some Asian
countries and the resulting economic slowdowns will cut into U.S.
exports and increase imports into the United States. Factories
here may eventually have to cut production and workers.
</P>
<P>
In another separate report today, the Labor Department said
that the number of applications for unemployment benefits dropped
by a bigger-than-expected 16,000 claims to 304,000 for last week.
The four-week average of claims remained stable at 308,750.
</P>
<P>
The report on factory orders showed that demand for durable
goods, items expected to last three or more years, increased by
1.6 percent. This was a sharp revision from an initial report last
week, which had put the rise in durable goods at 0.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Demand for autos was down 6.8 percent in January, and orders
for ships and tanks plummeted 68.5 percent, although this weakness
was offset by the strong gain in aircraft orders.
</P>
<P>
Demand for non-durable goods, including food and fuel, was down
0.9 percent in January, following an 0.8 percent increase in
December.
</P>
<P>
Orders for petroleum, coal and chemicals had the largest
decreases in the non-durable category. Warm weather caused by El
Nino has cut sharply the demand for heating fuel this winter.
</P>
<P>
Total orders for factory goods stood at 337.4 billion U.S.
dollars in January, 4.2 percent above the level of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of factory goods, which is regarded as a measure of
current production, dropped 1.0 percent, the third decline in the
last four months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
