<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Welcomes Lockerbie Ruling of Intl Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa welcomed the
ruling of the International Court of Justice (ICJ) over the
Lockerbie air disaster, the Foreign Affairs Department said in a
statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa regards the ruling of the International Court of
Justice as positive and a step forward toward a sensible and long
overdue solution," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The International Court of Justice, which is based in The
Hague, Netherlands, ruled last Friday that it has the authority
to try two Libyan suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing, thus
rejecting demands of the United States and Britain that the
suspects be tried in either country.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie, Scotland
killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa has always condemned terrorism in all its forms
and wishes to see those who have caused the suffering surrounding
the Lockerbie disaster brought to justice," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said South African President Nelson Mandela has confirmed
South Africa's support for the abrogation of sanctions that are
daily causing hardship for the people of Libya.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations banned flights to Libya after Tripoli's
refusal to extradite the suspects.
</P>
<P>
"South Africa will continue its support for the League of Arab
States (AL) and the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in this
matter and it shares with other like-minded countries the hope
that the ICJ's findings may herald the dawning of a new phase of
progressive and mature diplomacy in the world," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
The AL and the OAU have been supportive of Libya's position
that the trials should be held in a neutral country.
</P>
<P>
Mandela visited Libya twice in October 1997 in defiance of
Washington's strong opposition.
</P>
<P>
Libya brought the case to the international court in March,
1992, insisting that it should be allowed to try the men itself.
</P>
<P>
It later softened its stance to agree to hand the suspects for
trial in a third, neutral country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Claims 1,000 Lives Every Month in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 5 (Xinhua) -- About 1,000 South Africans
are killed every month by tuberculosis, South African Press
Association said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma as
saying on Thursday that 67,841 cases of TB were registered and
reported in the country during the first two quarters of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The figure for the whole of 1996 was 103,148, she said in
reply to a parliamentary question.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department said earlier this week that South
Africa's TB program was moving slowly and was not well focused,
effectively managing only four out of 10 patients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
