<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Govt Tones Down Red Meat Advice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The British government on Thursday
toned down health guidance on the link between red meat and
cancer.
</P>
<P>
The latest advice says that while those eating more than the
average 90 grams of red meat a day should consider a reduction,
those on no more than 90 grams need not change.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the Health Department said even those consuming
the average quantity should consider cutting down.
</P>
<P>
But the Committee on Medical Aspects of Food and Nutrition
Policy (COMA) said anyone eating over that amount should cut down
to reduce the risks of cancer.
</P>
<P>
"Adults who eat more than the average amount of red and
processed meat, especially those eating a lot more, might benefit
from a reduction," said Kenneth Calman, the government's Chief
Medical Officer and chairman of COMA.
</P>
<P>
This is a change from the committee's preliminary findings last
September which said those eating the average 90 grams a day
should also cut down.
</P>
<P>
The change is reported to follow a row between members of the
government committee looking into the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
