<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
was ready to meet with Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams but not until
after its exclusion from peace talks was over next Monday, a
government spokesman said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's spokesman said Blair would respond to Sinn
Fein's request for a meeting and the meeting would possibly take
place in the second half of next week.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of Irish Republican Army, was
barred from the peace talks late last month for IRA's involvement
in two killings early last month, but the party could regain its
seat if IRA takes no more terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein leader Adams denied any Sinn Fein links with the
killings and requested a meeting with Blair to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said a letter would be sent to Adams asking him
to come to the prime minister's London office for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Although the party is free to return to the talks next Monday,
it has said it will not do so until Blair grants its leaders a
face-to-face meeting. 
