<HEADLINE> France Welcomes Release of 100 Lebanese Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The release of some 100 Lebanese
prisoners by Syria makes up a gesture of opening by Damascus as is
wished by France and Europe, said French Socialist parliament
deputy Gerard Bapt on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bapt, who is chairman of the France-Lebanon Friendship
association, said the release came in the wake of "an unofficial
intervention" with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad by "a Syrian
friend" of France.
</P>
<P>
Bapt accompanies French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine in a
tour to Lebanon and Syria in January.
</P>
<P>
About 100 Lebanese prisoners, jailed by Syria since the
Lebanese civil war from 1975 to 1990, were returned to Lebanon by
Syria on Thursday, reported Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
Syria still detains 33 Lebanese charged with spying for Israel,
said AFP.
</P>
<P>
Before being returned to Lebanon, the prisoners were given a
verbal-verdict each by a Syrian court on whether they should stand
trial in Lebanon, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria have signed a pact of "brotherhood,
cooperation and coordination" which includes security
cooperations, and 35,000 Syrian troops are stationed in Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
