<HEADLINE> Senior Zimbabwean Official Calls for Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's National Planning
Commissioner Richard Hove Thursday called on the government and
trade unions to solve their diferences through talks, saying
dialogue is the best way to solve problems besetting the nation,
the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the job stayaway called for by the Zimbabwe
Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU), Hove said differences between
the government and the Trade Unions should always be temporary.
</P>
<P>
The ZCTU organized a two-day mass stayaway, which ended
Wednesday, in protest against the government economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Accoring to the Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries, the
country lost about 40 million U.S.Dolalrs in production in the
national strike.
</P>
<P>
''There is need for dialogue between the government, the civic
society and other stalkholders to resolve the economic problems
the country is currently facing,'' Hove said at an investment
conference in the central Zimbabwean city of Gweru.
</P>
<P>
''Whatever differences exist between any organisation and the
government,'' he said, ''people should not forget that the
country belonged to all of us''.
</P>
<P>
He stressed, ''We have a country for ourselves and for posterity.
Whatever differences exist let they not be permanent and result
in our country losing respect from the outside community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
