<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The average monthly salary of Israelis reached
5,805 shekels (1,626 U.S. dollars) in 1997, rising by 2.4 percent,
according to official statistics issued on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure applies to the foreigners working legally in Israel,
with the exclusion of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Official figures show that Lebanon earned 1 billion
dollars from tourism in 1997, which accounted for 30 percent of
the national income.
</P>
<P>
More than 553,000 foreign tourists visited Lebanon in the year.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon and Syria signed a three-year agreement on
commercial navigation to ease the movement of passengers and goods
on Monday, the Daily Star newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
A second cooperative accord involving engineers and officers
in merchant fleets and unifying legislation was also signed, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Officials and pharmacists of Lebanon and Syria
discussed plans for a common Arab pharmaceutical market on
Monday, according to the Daily Star.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have signed an agreement in the field and are
working to help create a common Arab market.
</P>
<P>
The issue will be discussed during a meeting of Arab health
ministers to be held soon in Syria.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Germany exported an estimated 5.4 billion dirham
(1.47 billion dollars) worth of goods to the United Arab Emirates
(UAE) last year, against 5.2 billion dirham (1.41 billion dollars)
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
German ambassador to the UAE Martin Schindler said the UAE,
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are the most important markets for German
exports in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The UAE and Germany have signed agreements to prevent dual
taxation and promote joint investment, technical cooperation and
air transportation between them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
