<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Iran's National Oil Company has announced that it
raised the price of ship fuel by 2 to 2.5 dollars per tonne from
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The price of the fuel shipped from the Kharg island rose from
62.5 to 65 dollars per tonne, while the price of the fuel shipped
from Bandar Masher was increased from 57.5 to 59.5 dollars.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The World Gold Council based in Dubai, UAE, said
in a statement that the demand for gold in the world in 1997
amounted to 2,935 tonnes, rising by 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The council attributed the increase to that of purchases in the
Middle East, India and other Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In the Middle East, Saudi Arabia topped the list of the gold
consumers. But the growth rate of its demand was at 8 percent in
1997, much less than that of the UAE, Kuwait, Bahrain, Oman and
Qatar, whose growth rate stood at an average of 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
MANAMA -- Bahrain recently opened a urea plant in Sotra, south
of the capital Manama.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the plant, an affiliation of the Gulf
Company for the Manufacture of Petrochemicals, cost 180 million
dollars, according to the company's Director General Mustafa
El-Sayed.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States would buy 100,000 tonnes of the
product annually during the coming five years.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- According to official figures, Jordan's exports to
Iraq in 1997 arrived at 120.6 million Jordanian dinars (170.37
million dollars), against 144.3 million dinars (203.46 million
dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has decided to build a world trade center in
Said, a Mediterranean port.
</P>
<P>
The center with an area of 10,000 square meters and 12 stories
will cost 30 million Egyptian pounds (8.82 million dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
