<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-05 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot President, EU Officials Meet on Accession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides Thursday held talks with the visiting European Union
(EU) External Relations Commissioner, Hans Van den Broek, to
discuss the Cyprus' accession issues.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was in the presence of British EU presidency
envoy Sir David Hannay, took place in view of preparations for
the upcoming start of Cyprus' accession negotiations with the EU
on March 31.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Van den Broek said he had exchanged
views with President Clerides and explained "what can further be
done to prepare in the best possible way for this event."
</P>
<P>
"We have been discussing ways and means to give as much
substance and operational significance to the conviction that the
membership of Cyprus should benefit both communities," the EU
official added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the prospects of the resumption of U.N.-led
talks on the political problem of Cyprus were also part of the
discussions Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
However, the EU official, who arrived here Wednesday night,
refrained from disclosing any details on a formula he discussed
with the Cypriot government officials for the Turkish Cypriot
participation in the forthcoming EU accession talks.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash has refused to see Van
den Broek and British envoy Hannay in protest against the EU
decision to start accession talks with the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
According to the conclusions of the Luxembourg EU summit last
December, the government of Cyprus is requested to include
representatives of the Turkish Cypriot community in the accession
negotiating delegation.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has proposed Turkish Cypriot
participation provided that the Turkish Cypriot side accepts the
principle of Cyprus' accession to the EU and the Turkish Cypriot
representatives are part of the Republic's negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over 37 percent of the island
in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side declared in 1983 a breakaway "the
Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which was only recognized by
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler-Benz Achieves Good Results in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Daimler-Benz AG today
announced an operating profit of 4.3 billion marks (2.4 billion
U.S. dollars) for 1997, up 78 percent from the 1996 level.
</P>
<P>
The company said that the higher profits came mainly from
innovations in all business sectors, progress made in boosting
efficiency as well as favorable currency developments.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, turnover of the group also jumped 19 percent to
about 124 billion marks (68.5 billion dollars) last year,
preliminary figures released by the company showed.
</P>
<P>
In a sector breakdown, the group's car division achieved
turnover of 53 billion marks (29 billion dollars) last year, the
commercial vehicle division 39 billion marks (22.5 billion
dollars), the aerospace division 15.3 billion (8.5 billion
dollars) and the services unit 15.5 billion marks (8.6 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Double-digit increases had been registered in all these
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Some 715,000 passenger cars and over 417,000 commercial
vehicles were sold by the company worldwide last year, both
representing new records, the company added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
