<HEADLINE> Sudan Accuses Eritrea of Shelling Its Territories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Sudan has accused Eritrea of
shelling its border villages in the eastern state of Kasala,
injuring a number of villagers and damaging some water resources
and schools, the official Sudanese news agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement published by the agency, a spokesman of the
Sudanese Armed Forces and Deputy Chief of Staff General Abdul
Rahman Sirrul Khatm said that the Eritrean artillery shelled the
Sudanese villages of Qasf, Abu Qaml and Hadra Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The shelling was aimed at schools and civilian sites, but no
pupils were killed or injured as the shelling started before
school day, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sudanese artillery responded to the shelling, he said, adding
that the fresh attack constituted a series of Eritrean aggressions
against Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The shelling was the second of its kind in less than one
week and the Sudanese-Eritrean border strip has been subjected to
military escalation over the past six months.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean ruptured its relations with Sudan in December 1994,
accusing Sudan of supporting its opposition group Islamic Jihad
Movement in its effort to overthrow Eritrean President Isaias
Afewerki.
</P>
<P>
On its part, Sudan has accused the Eritrean government of
giving shelter to armed Sudanese opposition groups, which use
Eritrean borders as springboard in attacking Sudanese military and
civilian targets in a bid to topple the Sudanese Islamic
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
