<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Starts European Tour to Win Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu left here Thursday for Madrid, starting a trip to four
Western European countries in a bid to win support for Israeli
policy on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day tour in Spain, Germany, Norway and Britain,
Netanyahu is expected to explain Israel's current effort to
resuscitate the peace talks with Lebanon and implement the related
U.N. resolution to withdraw troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Netanyahu said that "it is important
that the European leaders understand our position and perhaps as
a result they may agree with it. "
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that despite the great importance of
Israel's relationship with the United States, "Europe must not be
abandoned."
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu proposed last week that if Lebanese government could
ensure the security of Israeli northern border, Israel was willing
to fulfill U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 and withdraw its
troops from the buffer zone in south Lebanon, which it set up in
1985 to protect cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Although U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will be in
the United Kingdom when Netanyahu gets there, "nothing has been
said and nothing arranged", Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is also expected to enlist European leaders' support
in pushing forward the Israeli-Palestinian peace process, which
has been stalled for several months over the extent of Israel's
next pullback in the West Bank. 
</P>
