<HEADLINE> Zambia, New Zealand Urged to Identify New Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Foreign Affairs Minister
Keli Walubita Thursday called on Zambia and New Zealand to
identify new areas of cooperations in economic development to
enhance bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a dinner for New Zealand Foreign Minister Don
Mackinnon here Thursday, Walubita regretted that despite buoyant
bilateral ties, there is very little trade and economic
cooperation between them, the state-controlled Zambia National
Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Walubita expressed his government's gratitude to New Zealand
for its technical assistance and agricultural training provided
to a large number of Zambians.
</P>
<P>
He also spoke highly of the tremendous development achieved by
the New Zealand government since the end of the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
During the dinner given at the end of Mackinnon's two-day
visit to Zambia, Walubita briefed his New Zealand counterpart on
Zambia's reforms launched after the ruling Movement for
Multi-party Democracy (MMD) came into power in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The MMD government initiated economic reforms designed to
liberate the economic activities with a view to encouraging both
local and foreign investment and thereby free the market from the
state control.
</P>
<P>
These economic reforms, though stringent and painful to most
Zambians, especially the vulnerable groups, have started to show
signs of sustainability, said the Zambian foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some of the country's economic indicators such
as inflation and bank interests rates have ebbed to "manageable"
levels. 
</P>
