<HEADLINE> Lebanon Accuses Israel of Not Honoring UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz on Thursday accused Israel of not honoring United Nations
resolutions and refusing to return the occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before meeting with Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouq al-Sharaa, Boueiz criticized Israel for refusing
to accept the land-for-peace principle of the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The principle of trading land for peace is widely accepted as
the cornerstone of the peace process. But Israeli Prime Minister
Benyamin Netanyahu insists that the security of the Jewish state
should be guaranteed before making peace with Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister stressed that the resumption of
the peace talks between Lebanon, Syria and Israel depends on
Israel's commitment to the principle.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sharaa arrived in Lebanon on Wednesday to coordinate with
the Lebanese side about Israel's offer relating the issue of south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Demanding an unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon, al-Sharaa said Israel's proposal is a trap aimed at
driving a wedge between Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Israel has expressed its readiness to pull out of south Lebanon
if the Lebanese government agrees to curb attacks on Israel by
Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Israel is occupying a 1,200-square-kilometer area in south
Lebanon to allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border
attacks by Lebanese resistance forces which have been fighting to
drive Israeli troops out.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria agree to coordinate their positions on key
issues and not to negotiate peace with Israel separately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
