<HEADLINE> Angola Accuses Zambians of Backing UNITA Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Angola Thursday accused some
Zambians of supplying weapons to the rebels of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Angolan Ambassador to Zambia Manuel Augusto told a news
briefing here that some Zambians have been supplying weapons to
the UNITA rebels through Zambia's Ndola airport.
</P>
<P>
He Claimed that Zambian territory is used in many ways by
these Zambians who support UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Augusto said Angola will try in its own ways to ensure that
Zambian territory is not used by the former rebel UNITA movement.
</P>
<P>
He described the situation in Zambian-Angolan border as
serious, saying the border is almost under the control of UNITA.
</P>
<P>
But the ambassador denied that Angola has accused Zambia of
backing UNITA.
</P>
<P>
In January Zambian Foreign Minister Keli Walubita said his
country was committed to the peace process in Angola and had
worked hard for the implementation of the Lusaka protocol signed
by the Angolan government and the UNITA in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Walubita said Zambia has no intention of allowing its
territory to be used for hostile activities against any
neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
After Angola's independence in 1976 the UNITA fought a civil
war of nearly 20 years against the government. Although the two
sides signed the Lusaka peace accord which ended the civil war,
UNITA has been blamed for not abiding by it and peace has not
prevailed yet all over the country. 
</P>
