<HEADLINE> Hamas Activists Arrested in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel and Palestinian security
forces arrested more than a dozen Hamas members after uncovering
one of its cells in the West Bank on Thursday, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli General Security Service detained 15 Hamas
activists in West Bank cities of Ramallah, Nablus and Jerusalem,
the radio said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the arrestees were involved in two suicide
bombing attacks in Jerusalem last year, which killed 22 Israelis
and wounded 350 others.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian security force, meanwhile, arrested some other
Hamas members of the cell in Nablus. They were found to have been
planning a terrorist attack somewhere in central Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, or Islamic Resistance Movement, came into being in 1987
when the Palestinian popular uprising against Israeli occupation
broke out. It opposes realizing peace with the Jewish state as
long as the occupation of the Palestinian land does not come to an
end.
</P>
<P>
Terrorist attacks have bogged down the peace talks between the
Palestinians and Israelis, which have been stalled since March,
1996 when Israel broke ground for the construction of a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Israeli military court extended the
remand of another Hamas activist on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The court said the activist spoke openly about his attempt to
take hostages in a foreign embassy in Israel to bargain for the
release of Hamas prisoners in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Israel insists that its next troop pullback in the West Bank
depends on the fulfillment of the Palestinian commitments to fight
against terrorism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
