<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Wants UN Arms Embargo on S. Leone to Stay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- West African states have expressed
the preference to the retention of the U.N. arms embargo on
Sierra Leone even after other U.N. sanctions on the country have
been lifted, the News Agency of Nigeria reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This was made known by officials of the Committee of Five on
Sierra Leone under the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), who arrived in New York Tuesday to brief
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the Security Council on the
situation in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The retention of the arms embargo would be necessary until
disarmament was completed and security was reasonably established
in that country, said committee chairman Tom Ikimi, who is also
Nigerian Foreign Minister.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed arms embargo and travel ban on the
military junta in Sierra Leone after it ousted the legitimate
government through a coup on May 25 last year.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Security Council issued a statement on the
dislodgement of the junta from the capital Freetown and expressed
its desire to lift sanctions on the country after the
reinstatement of the elected government on March 10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
