<HEADLINE> Zambia's Detained Women Leader Charged with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's detained women leader
Nakatindi Wina who was allegedly involved in last October's
foiled military coup was formally charged here Thursday with
treason.
</P>
<P>
The charge was confirmed by police service spokesman Beenwell
Chimfwembe, the state-controlled Zambia National Broadcasting
Corporation (ZNBC) reported.
</P>
<P>
ZNBC quoted the spokesman as saying that Wina, the ruling
Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) Chairperson of Women
Affairs and parliament member, was charged Thursday morning along
with detained army officer Captain Stephen Lungu Alias Solo and
seven others.
</P>
<P>
Lungu is believed to be the mastermind of the coup. It was he
who on the early morning of October 28, 1997, announced the coup
on the State Radio after his men took its control.
</P>
<P>
All the nine charged with treason will appear at court Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nakatindi, wife of MMD National Chairman Sikota Wina, was
arrested on the night of January 27. She is the first and only
senior MMD official so far arrested in connection with the coup
aimed at toppling the government.
</P>
<P>
The arrest of MMD women leader comes in the wake of
investigations into the coup attempt in which the Winas' house
was reportedly implicated as having been the venue for the plot.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's security agencies have to date arrested over 90
alleged coupists, including former president and opposition
leader Kenneth Kaunda and another opposition leader Dean
Mung'omba.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, most of the coup-related detainees have been
charged. Among them, Kaunda was charged last month with
concealment of treason while 74 others were charged with treason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
