<HEADLINE> European Shares Mixed, London Keeps on Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe ended
mixed on Thursday, with London and Frankfurt extending their
losses while Paris bouncing back in late trade to end slightly
higher.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares closed 37.5 points
or 0.65 percent down at 5,695.6, having been down 104 points at
worst in the wake of a shock profit warning from U.S. computer
giant Intel Corp, which raised concerns over the outlook for
corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
The market took little comfort at midday from the Bank of
England's decision to leave the base interest rate unchanged at
7.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
It took a fairly resilient performance on Wall Street in early
trade to lift the London market out of the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares closed at 4,623.40, down 86.18
points or 1.83 percent as traders consolidated gains after recent
record highs and, with little market-moving domestic news,
investors were reacting to bearish international factors.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris closed slightly higher after bouncing
back in late afternoon trade from an early 1.5 percent dip, 14.48
points or 0.43 percent up at 3,395.80.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were supported by dollar movements against the
mark and other European currencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
