<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabbah to Take Full Charge of S. Leonean Affairs: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leonean President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah will be fully in charge of the country's affairs
after his reinstatement on March 10, west African countries have
reaffirmed.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi,
who is now in New York to brief the United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the Security Council on the
current situation in Sierra Leone, the News Agency of Nigeria
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the Council, Ikimi said President Kabbah, who has
lived in exile in neighboring Guinea since his ousting in a coup
last May, had indicated that the west African peace-keeping force
ECOMOG was required to provide security in the country in the
immediate future.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG was sent to Sierra Leone in the wake of the coup and
has been in charge of security in the country since it dislodged
the military junta about three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The activities of ECOMOG in that country would henceforth
depend on the assistance given it by President Kabbah, said
Ikimi, chairman of the Committee of Five on Sierra Leone set up
by the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) after
the coup.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that the duration of ECOMOG's stay in Sierra
Leone would depend on the time required for establishing peace
and security, especially the disarmament of combatants.
</P>
<P>
Although ECOMOG had already liberated a number of towns in the
hinterland from the junta forces, there was more work to be done
in that regard, he added.
</P>
<P>
The chairman urged the international community to move fast in
providing logistic support for ECOMOG's assignment.
</P>
<P>
He told the Security Council members that some countries in
the sub-region, such as Guinea, Ghana, Cote d'Ivoire, Niger and
Mali had indicated willingness to beef up ECOMOG forces but
needed financial support from the international community to
deploy their troops.
</P>
<P>
According to Ikimi, President Kabbah has expressed his
intention to ensure the total disarmament of all combatants,
reorganization of the army and rehabilitation of ex-combatants.
</P>
<P>
The president also wished to establish an inclusive government
and to down-size the government bureaucracy, taking full account
of the political and economic realities and the need for national
cohesion, rehabilitation and reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
In their individual responses, the Council members commended
ECOWAS for its job of ousting the junta and making arrangements
to reinstate Kabbah's legitimate government.
</P>
<P>
They agreed on the need for national reconciliation and the
provision of humanitarian assistance for Sierra Leoneans, who
they said had suffered immensely during the junta's rule.
</P>
<P>
The Council members also supported the idea of sending a U.N.
military observer mission to the country but pointed out that
such a decision would have to be based on a review of the
security situation there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
