<HEADLINE> UN Seeks Nigeria's Support in African Woman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Olara Otunnu, special
representative of the U. N. secretary-general on the effects of
violent conflicts on women and children, has solicited Nigeria's
support for achieving his mandate in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu, a citizen of Cote d'Ivoire, made the request at a
meeting with Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi, who arrived in
New York Tuesday to brief the U.N. on the situation of Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria reported Thursday that Otunnu said
he needed Nigeria's support because of the commendable role the
country had played in restoring peace to Liberia and Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
The special representative said he had done the basic ground
work for his assignment and was set to visit the areas affected
by wars, such as Sierra Leone and Liberia.
</P>
<P>
He said he intended to use the example of Sierra Leone as a
model for addressing the problems of women and children affected
by violent conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
"I am now ready to go to the affected areas and wish to begin
with west Africa, in recognition of the role that Nigeria has
played in Liberia and Sierra Leone," he stated.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is a main player in the resolution of the crises in
both Liberia and Sierra Leone, leading the west African peace
keeping force known as ECOMOG to restore peace in these two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Otunnu's major tasks as a special representative were to
create awareness of the plight of children and women in conflict
situations, mobilize communities to stop the abuses of women and
children in such areas.
</P>
<P>
He would also make specific proposals for humanitarian
assistance in war zones.
</P>
<P>
In response, Ikimi pledged Nigeria's assistance in the U.N.
official's effort to achieve his goals. 
</P>
