<HEADLINE> UN Arms Inspector Scott Ritter Returns to Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Scott Ritter, an American
U.N. arms inspector whose team was banned from doing work by the
Iraqi government in January, returned to Baghdad Thursday,
well-informed U.N. sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that Scott Ritter, with a 50-member U.N. team
from Bahrain, arrived at the Habaniya military airport, 80
kilometers west of Baghdad, Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Iraq had accused Ritter of being a spy with American Central
Intelligency Agency (CIA), implementing U.S. policy and trying to
create problems with the Iraqi side.
</P>
<P>
In mid January, Iraq barred a 16-member U.N. arms inspection
team led by Ritter from carrying out any activities in Iraq on
ground that the team, which was composed of nine Americans, five
Britons, an Australian and a Russian, lacked balance in its
composition.
</P>
<P>
The event led to the Iraq-U.N. crisis over weapons
inspection. On February 23, Iraq signed a deal with
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan that averted an imminent
U.S. military strike against Baghdad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
