<HEADLINE> Water Ice Exists on Moon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Chief scientist for NASA's
Lunar Prospector mission said Thursday afternoon that there are
significant amounts of water ice at both the north and south poles
of the moon.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing at NASA's Ames Research Center near Mountain
View, Calif., Dr. Alan Binder, project principal investigator,
said, "We think we are seeing something of 10 million tons to a
few hundred million tons of water."
</P>
<P>
Extracting water from the moon's surface to sustain research
teams, fuel spacecraft or power electrical-production systems
could cut in half the cost of future explorations to the moon or
Mars.
</P>
<P>
NASA's Lunar Prospector was launched to the moon on January 8
with the aim to find water on the moon. A month later, scientists
on Earth began to receive and analyze spectrographic data radioed
back by instruments aboard the craft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
