<HEADLINE> Horn of Africa Health Ministers Seal Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of health and heads
of health delegations in the Horn of Africa Thursday sign here a
protocol for cooperation on the cross border prevention and
control of major public health problems in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
At the 2nd Horn of Africa health ministers' conference held at
the Italian Cultural Institute here, the ministers of health and
heads of delegations have agreed, among other things, to address
the special needs of populations living in border areas with
specific regard to the control of tuberculosis, malaria,
leishmaniasis and eradication of poliomyelitis.
</P>
<P>
Opening the conference, Ethiopian Minister of Health Adem
Ibrahim said the seriousness and diversion of the major health
problems affecting the area should be dealt with common
strategies based on economic rationality and sustainability.
</P>
<P>
''The problem areas on which the conference has drawn its
attention is important because of the mere fact that their nature
of transmission largely depends on the living standard and
condition of the people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim added that ''we can proudly say that smallpox was
eradicated years ago. Why not tuberculosis, malaria, diarrhoea and
other communicable diseases from the Horn of Africa?''
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia and Kenya were represented by their ministers of
health while, Djibouti, Eritrea and Sudan sent senior health
experts.
</P>
<P>
The first Horn of Africa health ministers conference was held
in Addis Ababa in April 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
