Baghdad on Thursday called for a swift delivery of food and
medicine to Iraq to ease the sufferings of its people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Eric Falt, spokesman of the
U.N. Coordination Office for Humanitarian Affairs in Baghdad, said
the shortage of food and medicine in Iraq has been worsened due to
the delay of delivery.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the situation would further exert negative
effect on the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
He called on the international community to step up efforts to
transport food and medicine to Iraq as soon as possible in the
current third phase of the U.N.-Iraq oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Iraq began to implement the deal from December, 1996, under
which Iraq can sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil in every
six months. The U.N. has approved a resolution to increase the
amount to 5.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Falt added that Dennis Haliday, coordinator of the U.N. office,
has left Baghdad for New York to attend discussions on the new
food distribution plan in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The report of the U.N. office on implementing the third phase
of the oil-for-food deal will be submitted to the U.N. Security
Council next week, he said. 
</P>
