<HEADLINE> Abacha Urged to Run for Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian youths Thursday ended
their two-million-man rally in the capital Abuja with a call on
the current head of state, General Sani Abacha, to contest the
August 1 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
A copy of the resolution taken at the end of the massive
rally, which the Nigerian Television Authority said has attracted
more than two million people across the country, has been
presented to Abacha's political adviser in the early hours of
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, according to Alhaji Iliya Ibrahim, national
chairman of the National Council of Youth Associations of
Nigeria, which organized the rally, represented the collective
voice and desire of the youths in the country.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Sule Hamma, the political adviser who came to witness
the closing ceremony at about 5:00 Thursday morning, promised to
deliver the resolution without delay.
</P>
<P>
The rally, which began Tuesday morning, is seen as a major
move of pro-Abacha groups to press the head of state to announce
his decision to vie for the presidential election, which is to
end the five-year military rule on October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
To counter the government-supported rally in Abuja,
anti-Abacha groups also held one in the national economic center
of Lagos Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the anti-Abacha rally, which the organizer vowed
earlier would draw five million people from all over the country,
only attracted about 10,000 participants and onlookers, who were
dispersed by armed policemen in about half an hour's exercise.
</P>
<P>
With less than half a year to the presidential election, there
are only two individual politicians who have announced their
intention to contest.
</P>
<P>
The five political parties have not produced their own
aspirants.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the representative for the five parties commended
at the closing ceremony the Nigerian youths for their patriotism
to hold the carnival-like rally.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Abacha has kept silent on whether he would come out
to contest the forthcoming presidential election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
