<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Hibernia Halves Oil Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Canada's offshore oil megaproject
Hibernia has cut its output by half because of a maintenance
needed to revive the pressure of its wells, said a report
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Hibernia platform, which pumped 60,000 barrels a day in its
first phase of operation, is forecast to average 30,000 barrels a
day from late February until late June, according to the Globe and
Mail newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"We will take a dip in production over the next few months
until we get the pressure maintenance completed," Hibernia
president Harvey Smith was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The offshore project recently shut its first two wells for
reservoir maintenance and testing. But the third well has been
pumping almost 30,000 barrels a day for the past week.
</P>
<P>
The maintenance program of injecting water or natural gas into
wells is designed to help push out crude oil that's hidden deep
beneath the North Atlantic, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The offshore project went into production last November, 18
years after the huge Hibernia oil field was discovered east off
the Canadian province of Newfoundland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
