<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructuring Plan Draws Positive Response from Deputies (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The blueprint on institutional
restructuring of the State Council, a proposal submitted for
approval at today's meeting, has drawn positive response from
deputies at the First Session of the Ninth National People's
Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
It represents a pressing need for the restructuring of the
economy set-up and economic growth, and therefore it is an
imperative and popular move, -- this is a view shared by a lot of
deputies after being briefed on the plan this morning.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Xu Kuangdi, mayor of Shanghai, said China has undergone
profound changes in economic conditions since it has been shifted
from the traditional planned economy to socialist market economy.
Without the timely restructuring of government institutions and
change of functions, there would be negative impact on its future
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The plan submitted for approval by the State Council calls
for the reduction of ministries from 40 to 29.
</P>
<P>
"This is something we should have done earlier," said deputy
Hong Fuzeng, vice-chairman of Jiusan Society Central Committee,
one of eight non-Communist parties in China, in an interview. "It
will be a popular plan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Li Zibin, mayor of Shenzhen, a booming special economic
zone adjoining Hong Kong, said the remarks by State Councillor Luo
Gan on the restructuring plan was burst with responses this
morning. "This means the institutional restructuring is on the
minds of the people and it's urgent move," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite a thorough and detailed plan which conforms with
the requirements in economic development," said Li Chengyu,
vice-governor of Henan Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
