<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President on Asian Financial Crisis, Layoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin today
stressed the importance of viewing southeast Asian financial
turmoil in proper perspective and called for providing care to
workers laid off as a result of enterprise reform.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis afflicting some Asian countries since late
last year has lasted longer than expected, said Jiang at a group
discussion attended by deputies to the National People's Congress,
in session here since yesterday.
</P>
<P>
"China has not been seriously affected," he said. "But we
should have a correct understanding of the situation. We should
not underestimate its negative impact on our economy."
</P>
<P>
"We should see both its challenges for our economic
development and opportunities it may bring us," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We should be confident that we can fend off the crisis,
consolidate the current good situation at home and seek further
development as long as we follow the principles decided by the
central authorities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the priority for the country now is to do a good job in
developing the national economy and ensure that development be
fast and healthy.
</P>
<P>
Talking about state enterprise reform, Jiang said the central
government has formulated a series of policies for such reform,
which should be carried out in an earnest way.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called for governments at all levels to show care for
workers laid off as a result of state enterprise reform, and he
urged the launching of massive reemployment programs to provide
jobs for laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
"Reemployment programs have a direct bearing on the success or
failure of state enterprise reform and must be put on the agenda
of Party committees and governments at all levels," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called for creating more job opportunities. "Strenuous
efforts should be made to develop collective, self-employed and
private businesses and support medium and small enterprises so
that they can provide more jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president cautioned against laying off husband and wife at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
Governments should also formulate preferential policies to
encourage laid-off workers to find jobs by themselves or launch
their own businesses, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
