<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Calls for U.N. Debate on Kosovo Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
Friday called on the United Nations Security Council to hold an
urgent meeting to seek measures to stem further escalation of
violent conflicts in the Kosovo region of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Describing the situation in Kosovo as "highly explosive,"
Kinkel urged the U.N. to extend its military presence in the
Republic of Macedonia which borders Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
must also employ all available instruments of preventive
diplomacy, including sending its special envoy Felipe Gonzales of
Spain again to Kosovo and an expansion of the OSCE peace mission
in Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also called for an immediate meeting of foreign
ministers of the region with the international contact group
consisting of the United States, Russia, France, Britain, Germany
and Italy in a bid to seek coordinated actions in the region.
</P>
<P>
Germany had a special interest in seeking a solution to the
Kosovo crisis due to the presence of about 140,000 Kosovo-Albanian
refugees in Germany, Kinkel stressed.
</P>
<P>
"What is extremely necessary now is the beginning of a dialogue
between Belgrade and the ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo about
the future of the Serbian province," he said.
</P>
<P>
He repeated his warning that "Belgrade's return ticket to
Europe is dependent on its attitude on the Kosovo issue."
</P>
<P>
Kinkel also urged the militants of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
to stop terrorist activities, saying terrorism, provocation and
violence would not serve their cause and would not be tolerated by
the international community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
