<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Political Turf War Likely to Worsen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, March 6 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's political turf war
could turn for worse as the prosecution has been investigating
opposition lawmakers over their possible involvement in a smear
conspiracy against President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
The prosecution has launched a probe into the allegation that
the powerful Agency for National Security Planning (ANSP)
established a task force before the presidential election last
December to smear Kim Dae-jung, a presidential candidate of then
opposition, as a pro-North candidate.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported Friday that some lawmakers of the
opposition Grand National Party were involved in the the smear
plot masterminded by former ANSP high ranking officials, who
allegedly plotted to make use of a letter sent to Kim by Oh Ik-je,
the South Korean defector to the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) who once served as Kim's adviser.
</P>
<P>
In the letter published by the ANSP in the run-up to the
presidential election, Oh said DPRK leader Kim Jong-il wanted Kim
Dae-jung to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, President Kim's ruling coalition, of the National
Congress for New Politics and United Liberal Democrats, urged the
prosecution to uncover the truth behind scene that the ANSP and
the former ruling camp GNP exploited the DPRK to its advantage in
the elections.
</P>
<P>
However, the GNP reacted with tough words on Friday, saying it is a
political retaliation by the ruling camp against the GNP as the
investigation came just one day after the GNP refused to approve
President Kim's appointment of Kim Jong-pil as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"If the probe is politically motivated, our party will not sit
idle and we will strongly oppose it," said GNP spokesman Maeng
Hyung-kyu.
</P>
<P>
President Kim appointed his coalition ally Kim Jong-pil as
acting prime minister Tuesday after the GNP, the majority of the
South Korean National Assembly, or parliament, collectively cast
"unmarked" vote slips to veto the nomination of Kim Jong-pil as
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The GNP said it is illegal for the president to have named an
acting prime minister, vowing that it will take all legal and
political measures, including asking the court to issue an
injunction, to suspend the premiership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
