<HEADLINE> Non-Communist Parties Play More Important Roles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China's eight Non-Communist
parties are playing more important roles in China's political
life, according to leaders of these parties speaking at a press
conference sponsored by the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) National Committee, in session
here since last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He Luli, chairwoman of the Revolutionary Committee of the
Chinese Kuomingtang (RCCK) Central Committee, said that RCCK has
conducted investigations and research on a wide range of issues
relating to reform and opening up programs and offered relevant
proposals.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party and the government have set great store by
many of the proposals such as those on building a clear and honest
government and speeding up reform of the pension system.
</P>
<P>
At the current session of CPPCC, the RCCK has put forward
proposals on promoting a co-ordinated economic development along
the Bohai Rim and on promoting family planning among the country's
large transient population, she said.
</P>
<P>
China Democratic National Construction Association (CDNCA) has
suggested to the CPC Central Committee ways to avoid financial
risks, according to its chairman Cheng Siwei.
</P>
<P>
Xu Jialu, chairman of the China Association for Promoting
Democracy (CAPD) Central Committee, said his association has made
suggestions to the government concerning cultural and ethical
progress, education and publishing, among other matters. 
</P>
