<HEADLINE> Poland Prioritizing Bid for Entry Into NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw
Geremek said Thursday the prioritized diplomatic effort this year
is to seek the approval by NATO members for his country's entry
into the western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Parallel to the effort, said Geremek in his report to the
parliament on the government's current keynote foreign policies,
Poland will begin negotiations for gaining the country's
membership at the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The parliament later passed his report after eight hours of
deliberation.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said Poland will work to expand relations
with countries like the United States, Germany, France and Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Poland's status in its region relys on its significance in
NATO and the EU," Geremek said, adding his country hopes to work
together with the Czech Republic and Hungary on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
Poland will, as always, back the integration among the three
Baltic states -- Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, and will formulate
a policy toward these countries.
</P>
<P>
About relations with eastern neighbors, Geremek said Poland
hopes to have "friendly, equal and mutually beneficial" ties with
Russia and will further its strategic partnership with Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
In the same report, the foreign minister also expressed
willingness to expand economic relations with countries in Asia,
Africa and Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
