<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCHR: Actions Needed to Ensure Women's Rights Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The international community should
move from fine words to firm actions to ensure that the rights of
women everywhere are fully honored, United Nations High
Commissioner Mary Robinson said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mary Robinson, the United Nations High Commissioner for Human
Rights (UNHCHR), made the remarks on the occasion of the
International Women's Day to be celebrated on March 8.
</P>
<P>
"Human rights are women's rights too and the United Nations
must be the uncompromising guardian of women's human rights," she
said.
</P>
<P>
However, she said the words of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights coupled with those of the Vienna Declaration in 1993,
and that of Beijing in 1995 stand in sharp contrast to the daily
life of so many women.
</P>
<P>
"Women throughout the world have found that declarations and
conventions are not enough to guarantee their human rights," she
said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1.3 billion people living in poverty, 70 percent are
women; the majority of the world's refugees are women; female
illiteracy is invariably higher than male illiteracy; women and
girl children are becoming commodities in cross-border
prostitution rackets and the pornography industry.
</P>
<P>
Millions of girls are still subject to genital mutilation,
women are regular victims of domestic violence and they are often
targeted in armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The best hope for women to realize their human rights lies in
the efforts made by women themselves, said Robinson.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she promised her office is to take practical and
creative measures to help women realize their human rights, such
as civil and political rights, economic, social and cultural
rights and the right to development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Minister Admits Bank Crime Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- South African Safety and
Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi admitted that bank robberies in
the country last year had increased compared with 1996, The Star
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Trying to disperse doubts over the disparity between police
statistics for bank robberies and that produced by banks,
Mufamadi Thursday said the two accounts were different because
they covered different periods of time.
</P>
<P>
The Council of South African Banks (COSAB) said on Tuesday
that bank robberies had increased by 14 percent, from 408 in 1996
to 465 last year.
</P>
<P>
However, police records showed a 29.4 percent decrease.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi said the latest police data on bank robberies covered
the period from January to September 1997, while COSAB's figures
covered the whole year.
</P>
<P>
South African banks said they lost nearly 140 million Rand
(28.4 million U.S. dollars) in robberies last year, 29 percent
more than the amount lost in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The Department of Safety and Security and COSAB have a common
enemy, which they must fight together in order to end the scourge
of armed robberies," Mufamadi said.
</P>
<P>
Police statistics indicated that robberies with aggravating
circumstances had decreased, while ordinary robberies had
stabilized. But opposition parties rejected the figures, saying
they were not true.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Mufamadi told parliament that the South
African Police Service had achieved major successes in
investigating the spate of robberies involving large amounts of
money, identifying and arresting some key suspects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
