<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Party Official Stresses Development, Stability for Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Senior Chinese Party official Hu
Jintao said here today that the Tibet Autonomous Region in
southwest China must attach equal importance to economic growth
and social stability for its long-term prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Hu, a member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau
of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, made
the remarks during a panel discussion with the Tibet delegation
to the ongoing session of the Ninth National People's Congress,
China's legislature.
</P>
<P>
"We can't concentrate on economic growth without a stable and
orderly social environment and a political situation of stability
and unity; it's also out of the question to maintain long-term
stability without economic growth, social progress and improvement
in people's life," Hu told the lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Tibetan people to take a clear-cut stand to
maintain national and ethnic unity, and oppose any activity aimed
to split the motherland and undermine ethnic unity.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the autonomous regional government to broadly
conduct education on patriotism and ethnic unity in a
down-to-earth manner, and spare no effort to foster and train a
contingent of highly-competent officials with a Tibetan majority.
</P>
<P>
He said it is of great importance to unite patriotic people of
all ethnic groups and social sectors and combine their forces to
add impetus to the development of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"We must continue to carry out the religious policy of the
Communist Party and the government in real earnest," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that the Tibet Autonomous regional government
push forward reforms in accordance with local realities, and pay
full respect to the people's wishes while taking new reform
measures.
</P>
<P>
Hu, who once served as autonomous regional Party secretary in
Tibet, expressed his great concerns and solicitude for the
herdspeople in northern Tibet, who were inflicted by the worst
blizzards in decades in recent months.
</P>
<P>
"The local government should make good arrangements for
people's life in the disaster-stricken regions, and make efforts
to improve these regions' capability of preventing and resisting
future disasters," he urged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
