<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Urges Constructive Talks on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria Thursday urged the
conflicting parties in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province for a
constructive dialogue to prevent the crisis from worsening into a
regional security threat.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry said Bulgaria was deeply worried over the
possibility that the violence between Serbian authorities and
ethnic Albanians could spread into other parts of the region.
</P>
<P>
In a statement quoted by a Bulgarian Telegraph Agency report,
the ministry warned against the crisis in Kosovo could pose as a
threat against the security and stability of the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, a neighbor of Yugoslavia under which Kosovo is a
province, believed that other countries in the region should work
together to avoid further conflicts, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development Thursday, Joseph Lopez, the NATO
commander of forces in southern Europe, said the western military
alliance hoped to find a peaceful solution to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 people died the same day in a clash in the Srbica
region, about 30 kilometers west of Kosovo province's capital of
Pristina, said a report of Yugoslavia's Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo heightened last weekend when four policemen
and 16 Albanians were killed in an armed clash.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of Kosovo's
population, have been seeking independence from Yugoslavia since
1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
