<HEADLINE> Video to Help Soccer Referees in Paris World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- For the first time video cameras
will be introduce to the World Cup to help referees decide whether
a ball crosses the goal line, according to soccer's world
governing body FIFA here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
At FIFA has set the rules of soccer _ asked the English
Football Association to work with universities to develop
technology that might be used to avoid goalscoring controversies.
</P>
<P>
FIFA officials emphasized that the move is only a trial, and
that video evidence will not be used to judge other incidents,
such as tackles or handball.
</P>
<P>
Under the laws of soccer, the whole of the ball must cross the
whole of the line for a goal to be awarded.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, several goal-line decisions have proved
controversial.
</P>
<P>
In another decision, FIFA said that referees must send off any
player committing a tackle from behind that is deemed to "endanger
the safety of an opponent."
</P>
<P>
The move, which will come into force in time for this summer's
World Cup, will likely prove controversial as referees, players
and coaches have criticized earlier FIFA rulings that force
referees' hand in disciplining players.
</P>
<P>
FIFA will take action against any referee that fails to
automatically send off a player after such an incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
