<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Deputies Yearn For Reunification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Fan Zengsheng, a Taiwan-born
deputy to the on-going Ninth National People's Congress, said,
"Many of my friends in Taiwan described my decision on return to
the motherland in 1979 as an insighted move."
</P>
<P>
Fan, born in Taiwan in 1939, was a graduate of a marine
university in Taiwan and left to study in the United States in
1970s.
</P>
<P>
"I returned to the Chinese mainland in 1980 under the
inspiration of the 1979 US trip by Deng Xiaoping, who called the
students to return to the motherland and work and contribute to
its modernization program."
</P>
<P>
"At that time, my friends in Taiwan mocked at me and cursed me.
But I was convinced that China has a bright future and the
motherland will get reunified sooner or later," he added.
</P>
<P>
"People of Taiwan origin are fully confident in China's
reunification after the transfer of power in Hong Kong," said Fan,
who is now deputy director of the Shanghai Harbor Administrative
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Another Taiwan deputy, named Chen Weiwen, is currently working
at the Guangzhou University of Traditional Chinese Medicine which
has enrolled over 300 Taiwan students.
</P>
<P>
Liang Yanjun said, "I am proud of being a NPC deputy and have
the opportunity to participate in discussing state affairs."
</P>
<P>
A deputy, named Wei Lihui, said, "When I studied abroad in the
1980s, many of my relatives did not want to meet me, but they
invited me to dinner one after another today."
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan delegation has 13 deputies who represent some 34,000
Taiwan compatriots residing on the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Yang Guoqing, president of the All-China Federation of Taiwan
Compatriots, said, "After the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland in 1997, Macao will follow suit in 1999. And I hope
that Taiwan authorities will clearly see these changes."  
</P>
</TEXT>
