<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists on Economic Growth Rate (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists share the view
that China is able to achieve an eight percent economic growth
rate in 1998 as proposed by the government and offer ideas about
how to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
The economists are here attending the annual session of the
Nation Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), China's top advisory body.
</P>
<P>
An economic growth rate of five to six percent can be generally
regarded as "high," but for China, it is necessary to aim higher
since a one percentage point growth in gross domestic product
(GDP) would bring three to four million job opportunities. This is
a prevailing view from the economists.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Zhuoji, a Beijing University professor, enumerated a host
of factors that favor a growth rate of eight percent this year,
including record grain reserves and other important raw materials,
a high savings rate among the Chinese people, low inflation, and
more channels for enterprises to raise funds.
</P>
<P>
Xiao calculated that, to maintain a growth rate of eight
percent, there should be about 600 billion yuan worth of
additional demand for goods and services.
</P>
<P>
According to Xiao, three factors have a direct bearing on GDP
growth, namely investment, consumption and net exports.
</P>
<P>
"Since it is likely that China's exports will be affected by
the financial crisis in Southeast Asia and currency devaluation in
the Republic of Korea and since a slowdown in income increases for
both rural and urban residents since last year has resulted in
sluggish demand, growth has to be driven chiefly by increased
investment," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
