<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists on Economic Growth Rate (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xiao said China should strive to increase investment in capital
construction projects by more than 400 billion yuan in 1998. The
government should also direct people's savings deposits totaling
4.8 trillion yuan into investment areas.
</P>
<P>
Dong Fureng, also a well-known economist, said China has
gradually moved from a society of shortages to a buyers' market --
there are now more goods than people would like to buy. The
government should guide individual investors to put their money in
areas considered as new economic boosters.
</P>
<P>
In Dong's view, such new economic boosters are infrastructure
construction, new and high-tech, technical upgrading of
enterprises, environmental protection, farmland improvement and
irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
He Keng, deputy head of the State Statistical Bureau and Zheng
Bonian, director of Inner Mongolia Economic and Social Development
Research Center, called for launching more infrastructure
projects.
</P>
<P>
Investors can take advantage of cheap cement and steel to build
railways, highways, gas facilities and telecom facilities, they
said.
</P>
<P>
"This can have ripple effects boosting housing and auto
industries in addition to driving economic growth," He Keng said.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jinhua, minister in charge of the State Planning
Commission, announced not long ago that China will invest a total
of one trillion US dollars in fixed assets investment before the
end of the century to ensure economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Wu Jinglian, also a renowned economist, proposed fine-tuning
economic policies, saying the government should appropriately
encourage consumption by making credit available for car and
housing purchases (by individuals).
</P>
<P>
The economists also warn against doing two foolish things -- to
boost the production of unsellable goods by loosening credit and
to engage in repetitive construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
