<HEADLINE> Joint Committee Formed to Pave Way for Somali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 6 (Xinhua)-- Somali faction leaders, Hussein
Mohamed Aidid and Abdulkadir Mohamed Aden Zoppe, agreed upon the
appointment of a joint political and technical committee on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting between the two sides in the capital, the faction
leaders set off towards the implementation of the Cairo agreement
concerning the conflict settlement in Somalia's disputed
southwestern regions dominated by the Rahanwein communities.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued shortly after the meeting
on Thursday, the two sides have appointed the 11-member joint
committee chaired by a Rahanwein leader which will travel to the
regions of Bay and Bakol on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The members of the committee will pave the way for the
convening of the Baidoa national reconciliation conference due to
be held by the end of this month by separating the combatant
militiamen from both sides.
</P>
<P>
They will also work on the modalities in which a coalition
force would be deployed to replace Hussein Aidid's militiamen in
accordance with the Cairo peace deal singed on 21 December, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new coalition forces is said to be defending those regions
from what they called "the enemy" during the national meeting in
which an interim government for Somalia will be established.
</P>
<P>
The press release signed by the two leaders has called on the
people of Bay and Bakol regions to help the efforts of
pacification and reconciliation among the people in those regions
by the newly appointed joint committee.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Aidid and Abdulkadir Zoppe have also urged the people
in those regions to unify their strength against whatever is
threatening the security in the regions.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the two factions have appealed to the international
community to help the Somalis morally and materially in convening
the national reconciliation conference in Baidoa.
</P>
<P>
The two regions of Bay and Bakol have been a conflict zone
between the Rahanwein communities and Hussein Aidid's men since
late General Aidid invaded those regions early September, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place at a time when a series of consultative
meetings continue between Mogadishu's leaders in the capital in
an attempt of finding an inclusive administration for Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
A power sharing compromise still seems to be beyond the reach
of Mogadishu's faction leaders, observers said here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
