<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Supports Burundi's Demand for Lifting Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- France supports Burundi's demand for
lifting the economic embargo imposed on the central African state
by its neighbors, said Burundian President Pierre Buyoya Friday.
</P>
<P>
In meeting Buyoya at the Elysee presidential palace, French
President Jacques Chirac "deplored" the embargo extended by eight
African countries last month, said sources close to Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The embargo was effective 18 months ago after Buyoya came to
power in a bloodless coup staged by the Tutsi-led military to
overthrow the elected Hutu government.
</P>
<P>
"The French authorities have confirmed what they have always
said, that the embargo should be reviewed," said Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya, here since Wednesday for a three-day visit, said the
Hutus and Tutsis of Burundi are on the way of reconciliation "on
an internal and external level," and the Burundian government has
"very clear projects" for national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, French presidential sources said the meeting between
Chirac and Buyoya was "long and very trustful."
</P>
<P>
Buyoya briefed Chirac on "the primary results from the efforts
of his government for national reconciliation" and on the "grave
consequences from the embargo on his country," said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Buyoya also asked France to help seek aid from international
financial institutions and to provide aid in education, public
health and re-settlement of Burundian refugees driven out of their
homes during the three-year civil war starting October 1993.
</P>
<P>
At least 150,000 people have been killed in the civil war
between Hutus and Tutsis which devastated the country's economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
