<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Deputy Calls for Formulating Supervisory Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A legislator in east China's
Zhejiang Province said here today that he would set forth a motion
on the promulgation of a supervisory law at the ongoing First
Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The motion should list specifications concerning the guiding
principles, contents, scope, procedures to go through and methods
of supervision, said Lin Xicai, chairman of the Standing Committee
of Taizhou City People's Congress, who is attending the Ninth
NPC's First Session held in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
It should also standardize supervision over the deliberations
and approval of government work reports, economic and social
development plans, financial budgets and final accounts.
</P>
<P>
To date, some laws are still not fully enforced or implemented
to the letter in some areas and departments, he said. A small
number of officials even misuse their power and become corrupted,
to the detriment of the interests of the state and the people.
</P>
<P>
Enhanced supervision by the people's congress is absolutely
essential for putting an and to corruption and other social evils
by a few functionaries in the executive, legislature and judicial
departments in accordance with law, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted, supervision by the people's congress is an
important component part of the people's congress system and a key
factor to giving full scope to the role of this legal system. Yet,
he added, this is the weak link in the related work of the NPC.
</P>
<P>
Though the NPC and its Standing Commitare vested with the
supervisory power, there are still no detailed stipulations on the
content, procedures and methods of supervision. This has much to
do with the lack of a supervision law based on China's specific
conditions, Lin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
