<HEADLINE> Chinese Audience Enthusiastic About British Theater's Othello </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- On a Beijing stage tonight, when
Othello strangled Desdemona and uttered his famous lines, the
Chinese audience's long applause showed their understanding of and
interest in this drama classic.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,000 people crowded into the Children's Art Theater in
the center of Beijing for their first taste of the Shakespearean
tragedy in English (with Chinese subtitles) performed by a British
troupe. The play, which was written in 1604, about the love of a
Moorish military leader for a girl of noble birth, is being
performed by the Royal National Theatre, the world's foremost
group of its kind.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Shakespeare enthusiasts milled around outside the
theater looking for a last-minute chance to get in, even after the
performance had started, because the tickets were all gone a week
ago.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yong, a teacher from the nearby city of Tianjin, who made
it to the theater after a two-hour drive, said, "Shakespeare
belongs to the whole world, and his works are a perfect study of
manipulation and human vulnerability."
</P>
<P>
Martin Davidson, a Counselor at the British Embassy in Beijing,
told Xinhua that the performance is the most important cultural
exchange program between China and Britain since the handover of
Hong Kong on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Othello" is part of a series of exchange activities in
accordance with a Sino-British cultural affairs agreement. The
Royal National Theatre's performance of "Othello" debuted in Hong
Kong last week, where it was warmly received, Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
Britain and China will have further exchanges this year in the
economy, science and technology, education, and culture, and the
drama is a good start, Davidson said.
</P>
<P>
A dozen Chinese theaters and art troupes that are interested in
Shakespeare have put on Chinese versions of his most renowned
plays, including "Hamlet," "A Midsummer Night's Dream" and "The
Taming of the Shrew."
</P>
<P>
Li Moran, a leading Chinese dramatist, played the role of King
Lear 12 years ago, but, he's never witnessed a Shakespeare play
performed by dramaists from Shakespeare's own country, he said. He
spoke highly of David Harewood, the black dramatist who is
playing the title role, for his excellent acting and understanding.
</P>
<P>
For the past two months, Britain and China have had a number of
exchange programs in education, publishing, and the arts, sources
from the British Council in China and the China Performing Arts
Agency of the Chinese Ministry of Culture, who organized the
performance, said.
</P>
<P>
In its 35 years of existence, the Royal National, which was
Established in October 1963, has gained a formidable reputation
worldwide for the work by its people, like Sam Mendes, the
artistic director of "Othello," and Laurence Olivier, the first
director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
