<HEADLINE> Tibetan Language Fit for Use on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Successful coding has made the
Tibetan language fit for use on the Internet, according to a
deputy to the National People's Congress, in session here since
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan has thus become the first language of an ethnic
minority in China to be usable in a computer age.
</P>
<P>
According to Deputy Jamyang Losang Jigme Tubdain, who is a
Tibetan from Gansu Province, a Tibetan-Chinese bilingual
information system has been successfully developed by more than 20
computer specialists and Tibetan teachers of the Northwest China
Institute of Nationalities.
</P>
<P>
A major component of the system is computer-oriented coding of
the Tibetan language, he said.
</P>
<P>
Other components of the system include designs of typefaces for
Tibetan characters, a data-bank relating to King Gesser -- a
well-known Tibetan epic, and Tibetan medicine-related data and
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
The system has been assessed as up to standard by a group of
specialists, according to Jamyang.
</P>
<P>
A living Buddha, Jamyang is head of the Lapuleng Monastery in
Gansu.
</P>
<P>
The information system is expected to help promote the
development of information technology in areas inhabited by the
ethnic group as well as information exchanges in the Tibetan
language, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
