<HEADLINE> Qatar Warns Against OPEC Meeting in Hurry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has warned members of the
Organisation of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) against
hurrying into holding an emergency meeting this month, the
official Qatari news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to other OPEC states, Qatar's Energy Minister
Abdullah Bin Hamad al-Attiya said the chances for the success of
such a meeting would be "very slim" unless "careful preparations"
were made, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members should clarify the objectives of the meeting with
guarantee in mind to completely adhere to their oil output quotas
awarded by the bloc, the minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The letter came after OPEC Secretary General Riwanu Lukman
invited the group's 12 members to attend a scheduled four-man
monitoring committee meeting in Vienna on March 16 to discuss
ways of propping up sagging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The prices have lost by more than 30 percent in the past four
months and crashed down to 14 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
The price collapse was due to ample supplies and declined
demand in world markets, which were triggered by OPEC's November
decision to raise its combined output ceiling by 10 percent to
27.5 million barrels per day, a mild winter in northern
hemisphere as well as Asia's economic turmoil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
