<HEADLINE> Satellite Data Now Available on Plantation Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China's State Bureau of Surveying
and Mapping (SBSM) began releasing a satellite picture depicting
the country's plantation situation on a monthly basis this year.
</P>
<P>
The satellite picture, with a survey precision of 1 square
kilometer, provides accurate information on the location and
growing situation of the plantation, which can be used as research
data for analyzing and predicting crop-growing situations and the
prevention of, or response to, natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological satellite data receiving station of the SBSM
is able to map out a picture of the plantation each month, whose
data will be stored in a compact disc and made available to the
public.
</P>
<P>
Research and analysis of satellite data play an increasing role
in helping people keep up with global environmental changes and
prevent natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
The data obtained by meteorological satellites has provided an
important basis for wide-range monitoring. 
</P>
