<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Working in Cities Return Home to Make Fortune (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- To people in Hongshan village in
east China's Anhui Province, farmer Zhu Xuncai is more mature and
far-sighted after nine years of doing transient jobs in large
cities such as Shanghai and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
This year, after a short reunion with families during China's
traditional Spring Festival, Zhu didn't go to urban areas as he
had formerly done every year. What he did instead was talk with
local officials about buying a timber mill in their small village.
</P>
<P>
"There is no need to make a fortune outside; my hometown also
has many opportunities," he said, admitting that cities still have
some attractions.
</P>
<P>
He plans to invest 2.1 million yuan in the mill and employ 110
farmers from the village.
</P>
<P>
Zhu had been one of the millions of surplus laborers in China's
rural areas who left their home for cities to make more
money. Their urban flow had set off a surge of transient workers
since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Now, the wave has entered a new stage where an increasing
number of former transient workers returned home from the cities
to start their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
Government statistics show that 80 million farmers go to urban
areas every year, but 15 percent of those return.
</P>
<P>
A survey by Anhui's agricultural sector shows that 37.6 percent
of the province's 4 million farmers now working in cities want to
return their hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Releases Second Weekly Air Quality Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's latest weekly air
quality report revealed that the Chinese capital continued to
suffer from comparatively poor environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
The city's air pollution index for the period between February
27 and March 5 stood at 203, with the ranking indicating a medium
pollution level.
</P>
<P>
Nitrogen and oxygen compounds constituted the major pollutants,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Beijing began issuing weekly air quality reports last week,
with the first report showing an index of 206.
</P>
<P>
China's National Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA)
classifies air quality in five grades, with an index of under 50
representing good environmental conditions. Relatively good
conditions fall between 50 amd 100; slight levels between 101 and
200; medium levels between 201 to 301; and serious pollution over
300.
</P>
<P>
"The use of coal and motor vehicle emissions are the major
factors creating pollution in Beijing," according to Zhao Yixin,
director of the local environmental protection bureau.
</P>
<P>
The city ranks first amongst capital cities worldwide with
annual coal consumption standing at 28 million tons.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the city has over 1.2 million motor vehicles, up
three-fold on only ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
Municipal authorities plan to extend great efforts to improve
the air quality over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Some 27 other Chinese cities, including Nanjing, Shanghai,
Dalian and Xiamen, currently release weekly air quality reports.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Take Measures to Deal With Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will have more severe
water rationing for homes and farms since the island is suffering
from the worst drought in its history.
</P>
<P>
Cypriot Minister of Agriculture, Natural Resources and
Environment Costas Themistocleous has declared water emergency on
the island, local press reports said Friday.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted as saying that "we are really in a very
difficult situation. The dams are nearly empty. So, we have to
take some measures in order to reduce the supply of water."
</P>
<P>
According to an assessment by the Water Development
Department (WDD), all reservoirs on the island now hold only 12.2
percent of their capacity, with a mere 33 million cubic meters of
water.
</P>
<P>
Dam inflow from rainfall runoff totaled only 12.7 million
cubic meters this meteorological year, compared to a 10-year
average annual inflow of 87 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
This east Mediterranean island mainly relies on rainfall for
its water supply.
</P>
<P>
Haris Omorphos, spokesman for the WDD, said that the drought's
bite and its tenacity, which is now in its fourth year, make it
the worst dry spell in Cyprus history.
</P>
<P>
"There is no other way to solve the problem, except to reduce
the supply of water below current levels, mainly in the
agricultural sector and also in the housing sector," Omorphos
said.
</P>
<P>
He expected the Council of Ministers (cabinet) will soon study
the situation and announce a new water rationing regime.
</P>
<P>
Other measures taken to solve the water shortage problem
include a plan to build a second seawater desalination plant.
</P>
<P>
The government also plans to continue subsidizing borehole
drilling to provide homes with water for toilets (underground
water is not suitable for drinking) and it will make available
recycled waste water for any crops.
</P>
<P>
The WDD is now planning to complete a pipeline by the end of
March, linking between the Dhekelia desalination plant on
southeastern coast and Nicosia, to carry desalinated seawater to
the capital.
</P>
<P>
The Dhekelia desalination plant, which was operational early
last year, will raise the output to its maximum of 40,000 cubic
meters of water a day from the current 20,000 cubic meters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Working in Cities Return Home to Make Fortune (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Like Zhu, Xu Licun returned home to Anhui in 1994 after three
years of working in Shenzhen as a salesman. With the support of
the local government, Xu contracted for a state cold-storage plant
in his hometown and changed it to a privately owned forage mill.
</P>
<P>
After three years, Xu's mill is now capable of producing 40
tons of forage per day. Recently, he also invested 1 million yuan
to set up branches in other areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
Xu's long-term plan is to turn his mill into the largest in the
province.
</P>
<P>
With experience, money and -- more importantly -- a broadened
horizon obtained from working in urban areas, these formerly
transient workers have become a new driving force for rural
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Incomplete statistics show that 100,000 workers have returned
to Anhui to start their own businesses, absorbing 700,000 rural
laborers and producing an annual output of 5 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels have become aware of this new
trend. China's central government has asked local bodies to guide
these local entrepreneurs on the track of healthy development and
protect their enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the wave of transient workers has caused
instability in urban areas and Spring Festival transport problems
as workers migrated home for the holiday. To solve these problems,
China defines its policy as encouraging an "orderly flow" of rural
surplus laborers and for them to seek opportunities in their
hometowns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African FM Ends Visit to Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo Friday wound up his three-day visit to
Ethiopia during which the two countries discussed further
strengthening of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Nzo and his Ethiopian counterpart Ato Seyoum
Mesfin discussed the political, economic and social developments
in the two countries and they agreed to intensify the cooperation
between the two countries in various fields, a joint communique
issued Friday by the two governments said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also signed a declaration of intent on
wildlife management cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They requested that a draft trade cooperation agreement and a
draft agreement on cooperation in the economic, scientific,
technical and cultural fields be finalized by the respective
relevant departments.
</P>
<P>
The ministers discussed regional and international issues of
common concern and agreed to enhance cooperation in preserving
continental peace and stability, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Somalia, the two ministers called on the
Somali people to engage in a direct and peaceful political
dialogue to bring about a just and lasting peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Nzo, who arrived at Addis Ababa Wednesday, also met Ethiopian
President Negasso Gidada, Prime Minister Ato Meles Zenawi, and
Speaker of the Council of Peoples' Representatives, Auto Dawit
Yohannes. 
</P>
