<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal's Transit Route to Bangladesh Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has agreed
to extend Nepal's use of a transit route running through India to
Bangladesh, The Kathmandu Post said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"A letter from Indian authorities informing us about the
extension granted to the Phulbari (transit route) has been
received," the daily quoted Nepali Foreign Secretary Murari Raj
Sharma as saying.
</P>
<P>
But he did not mention the duration of the extension.
</P>
<P>
The Indian Embassy in Kathmandu said in a statement that the
operating mode of the route will remain the same as before pending
a review.
</P>
<P>
The Kakarvitta-Phulbari-Banglabandh transit route, long-awaited
for land-locked Nepal, was granted by Indian Prime Minister Inder
Kumar Gujral in early June last year as a good-will gesture during
his visit to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The transit route runs from Kakarvitta, Nepal's eastern gateway
to India, to Phulbari in northeastern India and then to
Bangladesh's Mongla port.
</P>
<P>
The transit route went into operation on September 1, 1997, on
a six-month trial basis.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said however that instead of boosting Nepal's
trade with Bangladesh and other countries as expected, the transit
route remained idle most of the time due to the small number of
trucks and containers on the Nepalese part and other problems.
</P>
<P>
Much of Nepal's foreign trade is still dependent as before on
India's Calcutta port.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
