<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portion of 1,000-Year-Old Letter Located in U.S. Auction House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese cultural relics expert
today appealed for the return of a piece of a treasured ancient
letter, which was found recently in the New York branch of
Christie's auction house.
</P>
<P>
Christie's was scheduled to sell its portion of the letter
written by an ancient Chinese duke for an opening bid of 300,000
U.S. dollars on March 24, said Cao Jinyan, vice-curator of the
Zhejiang Museum.
</P>
<P>
A careful examination by experts determined that the piece of the
letter in New York and the one with two dukes' handwritings in the
Zhejiang Museum have the same origin and date back 1,000
years. The two pieces became separated more than 600 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The two parts of the document, regarded as a national treasure,
were reunited in Shanghai on March 2 for a cultural relics
appraisal. Cao expressed his hope that Christie's sale of the
letter is delayed until funds are raised for its return to China.
</P>
<P>
According to Cao, Christie's in an auction notification in
early February asked the Zhejiang Museum whether it was willing to
compete with other buyers. Qian Chu, writer of the letter who was
on the throne between 948 and 978, governed the area which is part
of modern Zhejiang Province in east China.
</P>
<P>
In its notification by mail, Christie's stated that the letter
to be auctioned bore seals, signatures and annotations by 43
well-known ancient Chinese painters.
</P>
<P>
The Zhejiang Museum responded that it owns a precious piece of
handwriting which might be related to the Christie's property.
</P>
<P>
After consulting the Complete Works of Chinese Fine Arts, which
has the picture of the letter, the auction house's experts
confirmed that they are twins.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, their Shanghai meeting proved the correlation in
paper, printing and calligraphic style.
</P>
<P>
Qian, the duke of the Wuyue Kingdom, handed down the letter to
his descendants, who had separated the original copy during war years.
</P>
<P>
One of the descendants donated a piece of the letter to the
museum in 1951. But the other half had been lost for hundreds of
years.
</P>
<P>
"I extremely hope that the other part of the national treasure
will come back to its homeland," Cao said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
