<HEADLINE> Tanzania's MPs Call for Probe into Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 6 (Xinhua) - A group of members of the
Tanzanian National Assembly have requested their Speaker Pius
Msekwa to summon the Legal and Constitution Committee to probe
the recent police killings of unarmed citizens, local media
reports Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Idrissa Msabaha, supported by the signature of 22
colleagues in the parliament, told a press conference Thursday
that the recent acts by the armed police anainst unarmed
citizens, with some causing deaths in Kigoma, Morogoro,
Kilimanjaro, Arusha, Mbeya and Dar es Salaam regions, had
promoted them to make the appeal to the Speaker.
</P>
<P>
"These inhuman acts to the people should not be condoned as
they are grossly violationg the fundamental human rights to
life," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Msabaha demanded Speaker Msekwa to convene the meeting
before the next Parliamentary session scheduled for April in
Dodoma to investigate among others whether the police killings
could be avoided.
</P>
<P>
He said that the proposed meeting would also investigate
whether laws governing the use of arms by the police were
followed during their operations.
</P>
<P>
In February, police opened fire on a rioting group near a
downtown mosque in Dar es Salaam, killing two people in the first
bloody and large-scale confrontation between police and citizens
since Tanzania's independence in 1961.
</P>
<P>
In northern Arusha region, police reportedly killed six
suspected bandits also in February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
