<HEADLINE> UN's Angolan Peace Proposal Still Not Accepted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government and the
former rebel forces, the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA), have not accepted the new
proposal suggested by UN official here after two day's heated
discussion.
</P>
<P>
The proposal put forward by UN Deputy Representative Behrooz
Sadry on March 3, said that UNITA should guarantee to be totally
non-militarized by Thursday, and the government declares UNITA as
a legal political party by Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 12-points proposal also outlines that the UNITA radio
station to stop broadcasting by Saturday and the UNITA military
dismantle all its forces by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The government and UNITA, which have been discussing the
proposal under the mediation of UN peace observation group and
the Portuguese and Russian representatives, hold different views
mainly on the time for the dismantle of UNITA forces.
</P>
<P>
The government also insisted that UNITA, as an independent
political party, should not have its own military forces.
</P>
<P>
But UNITA representative at the joint committee of the Angolan
peace process, Isaias Samakuva, said that UNITA has never
promised to issue a non-militarization communique.
</P>
<P>
Samakuva said that UNITA would issue such a communique, but
not on March 5 as said in the UN proposal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
