<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, U.N. Launch Project to Cut Post-Harvest Grain Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, radiation technology provides an environmentally clean
way to reduce infestations and quarantines of bulk grain being
imported or allocated through ports.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP will grant 452,000 U.S. dollars of assistance to the
project, which will be implemented by the Tsinghua Science Park of
Tsinghua University.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, a grain radiation facility will be
installed at the Fangcheng port of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region in Southwest China, one of the country's most impoverished
areas.
</P>
<P>
The radiation facility is expected to handle one million tons
of grain a year and reduce post-harvest grain losses by 100,000
tons, which is enough to feed 400,000 people.
</P>
<P>
With financial assistance from the World Bank, Fangcheng is
becoming the largest grain transportation hub in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Grain going through the port, which has an annual handling
capacity of 1.6-to-2.15 million tons, will go to 120 million
people in Guangxi, as well as Yunnan and Guizhou provinces. 
