report of 1997/98 to the parliament Thursday, Meles said if the
present trend continues Ethiopia will be a country with inflation
below one percent for three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Meles said the revenue the country has derived from foreign
trade in the last six months exceeds by 24 percent the sum
obtained over the same period of last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
"If this persists in the coming six months, the country would
be able to register an over 20 percent growth in its foreign
trade for three consecutive years," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meles said the national production growth is expected to be
lower this year due to a fall in agricultural production owing to
rain failure and untimely rains.
</P>
<P>
He said agricultural production is expected to dwindle this
fiscal year as a result of rain failure precipitating food
shortage in the various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said food secured in aid and purchased with government
budget is being rationed among the needy in the drought affected
areas, adding that no casualty has so far been reported from the
drought affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The small rain season (February-May) rains this year has
started off well, he said, and added that central and regional
governments have joined efforts in distributing selected seed and
fertilizers to help farmers make the best use of the rain.
</P>
<P>
Concerning the budget, Meles said government has collected in
the first six months 3,438 million Birr (494 million U.S.
Dollars) in revenue accomplishing 49 percent of its annual
target.
</P>
<P>
He said government expenditure totaled 3,227 million Birr (464
million U.S. Dollars) accounting for 32.6 percent of its annual
plan, adding that untimely rain and delay in construction works
have forced the expenditure to fall below the target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
