<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Nigeria Enters Vital Stage of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 6 (Xinhua) -- As the Nigerian military government
transition to civil rule program is close to the end, Head of
State General Sani Abacha will in "a few weeks' time" decide
whether or not to contest the August 1 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
The decision is to break the impasse in the country's
political development as there are less than five months to go
and no presidential candidate has been produced.
</P>
<P>
With increasing request for Abacha to run the race, the head
of state will be engaged in consultations with his colleagues,
friends and family members before making any decision, according
to Abacha's political adviser Alhaji Sule Hamma.
</P>
<P>
Hamma disclosed this at the closing earlier Thursday of the
two-million-man rally in the capital Abuja, an important move by
pro-Abacha groups to draft him to the race.
</P>
<P>
Hamma assured the Nigerian youth that Abacha was not the type
of leader who would disappoint the nation when faced with hard
decisions.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Abacha has over the past four years received
countless appeals from representatives of the people from all
sections and sectors that he present himself for election.
</P>
<P>
However, Abacha has kept silent till today, a posture many
observers believe to wait for the right time to make an
announcement.
</P>
<P>
Now the time is there as the massive carnival-like rally is
seen as the high tide of the appealing campaign, and Abacha could
find nowhere to go but to make known his decision on this matter.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the head of state, who came to power in 1993, could
not afford to delay further since there are less than five months
to go before the presidential election begins on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Despite the intention expressed by two individual politicians
to contest, all the five political parties have not yet produced
their own aspirants, probably waiting for Abacha's decision.
</P>
<P>
They even met not long ago to discuss whether or not to have
Abacha as their consensus presidential candidate. The meeting did
not witness an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Abacha military administration has promised to hand over
on October 1 to an elected civilian government.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Abacha rally was organized by the National Council of
Youth Associations of Nigeria and gulped 500 million naira (about
six million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Although at least three people lost their lives due to traffic
accidents on their way to the capital, the 48-hour rally was held
in good order, thanks to the support of the government.
</P>
<P>
However, an anti-Abacha rally organized by pro-democracy and
human rights groups was dispersed by the police in the national
economic center of Lagos Tuesday before it really began.
</P>
<P>
Support or oppose Abacha to run for presidency, the country's
transition to civil rule has entered its final stage. Whether the
coming civilian government is widely accepted will affect the
political situation and socio-economic development of the country
in both the short and long run.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
