<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fake Invention Found in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The so-called century invention
that could allegely find hidden water, buried treasure and land
mines, and even identify criminals by their handwriting, has been
found by Lebanese police to be fake.
</P>
<P>
The bogus device that has hoodwinked people in Arab countries
was demonstrated here Thursday to reporters in the presence of the
suspect, Nassar Bin Omar Mahmoud Said, local English-language
newspaper Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"I don't regret what I did because the whole thing was a
joke," said Said.
</P>
<P>
The 41-year-old suspect had promised to lend Kuwaitis his
device to remove mines left by Iraq during the 1990-91 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
He is believed to have also promised to help Egyptian
explorers locate a French ship that sank off the Egyptian coast
last century and is believed to have been carrying precious
stones.
</P>
<P>
The device emitted a beam of red light which supposedly beeped
when touched on the target. But the beeper was commanded by a
small remote control held in the suspect's shoe and operated by
his toe.
</P>
<P>
Said claimed that one of his main aims was to gain Lebanese
nationality "which I heard is easily granted to inventors." But
the paper didn't say where the suspect was from.
</P>
<P>
The fraud was revealed last week when a state security cadet
stole the apparatus and was sued by Said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
