<HEADLINE> Indian carpet Exporters Hire Lobbyist in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Indian carpet exporters have
hired a lobbyist in the United States to safeguard their interests
threatened by activists campaigning against child labor, an Indian
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Business Standard said the Carpet Export Promotion Council
(CEPC), an organization of Indian exporters in Washington, signed
a contract with Powell, Goldstein, Frazer and Murphy LLP (PGFM), a
Atlanta-based law firm.
</P>
<P>
The urgency for hiring the lobbyist arose out of a lawsuit
filed recently by a non-governmental organization, the
International Labor Rights Fund (ILRF), under a new U.S. law that
bans the import of carpets made by children in bondage.
</P>
<P>
Indian exporters, alarmed by the ILRF demand for a blanket ban
of hand-knotted carpets from South Asia, visited the United States
twice in February to meet U.S. customs and treasury officials to
"tell their side of the story".
</P>
<P>
If the demand of the ILRF was accepted, it would harm India's
carpet industry seriously, whose exports were of the order of 600
million U.S. dollars, including 175 million U.S. dollars to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The United States imported carpets worth 329 million U.S.
dollars last year. India is the largest carpet exporter to the
Unite States followed by China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Temple Fair To Be Launched at Scenic Wudang Mountain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Scenic Wudang Mountain will become
the venue for a grand temple fair to be held at the end of this
month to mark a major Taoist festival.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 pilgrims from across China and from Singapore,
Japan, Thailand, the Republic of Korea, France, and Germany will
gather at the Taoist mountain in Hubei Province to mark the
birthday of the northern god worshiped by the Wudang sect of
Taoism. The legendary figure's birthday falls on March 3 of the
lunar calendar, which is March 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
This year's celebration will begin on March 28 and end on March
31. The four-day event will feature religious rituals, martial
arts shows and trade fairs.
</P>
<P>
Mount Wudang is on the list of the world cultural and natural
heritage sites of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization.  
</P>
