<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Price Cutting Makes Consumers More Affordable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Dramatic price cuts sweeping
the personal computer industry makes U.S. consumers more
accessible to desktops and laptops.
</P>
<P>
The cutting also makes powerful notebook computers affordable
for students, small-business owners and even consumers.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that laptop computers, which now account
for less than 20 percent of all PC sales, could become mainstream
machines within the next year.
</P>
<P>
Although more expensive than desktops with comparable
technology, one can now buy a notebook fully capable of handling
most computering jobs with 1,500 U.S. dollars or so.
</P>
<P>
IBM, a leading notebook giant, unveiled a 1,599-dollar
ThinkPad, one of several lower-cost notebooks that the company has
introduced as part of a campaign to target the retail market.
</P>
<P>
The new model is powerful ennough to do word processing and
spreadsheets, or for using e-mail and the Internet, accordind to
IBM.
</P>
<P>
Also this week, Compaq Computer, the No.1 seller of PCs,
slashed prices across its entire line of notebooks designed for
business users.
</P>
<P>
Price cuts for notebooks have been in some cases even more
dramatic than for desktops, with a notebook costing 5,000 dollar
a year ago now only cost 2,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
