<HEADLINE> UN Arms Inspections Led by American Ritter Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A 50-member arms inspection group
of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarmament in Iraq led
by American Scott Ritter started its inspection work in Iraq on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that the team led by Ritter, which
arrived in Baghdad Thursday afternoon, made a routine inspection
tour of some Iraqi weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
Iraq called Ritter "trouble-maker" and accused him of being a
spy with U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), implementing
U.S. policy and trying to create problems with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In mid-January, Iraq barred a 16-people team headed by Ritter
from carrying out any activities in Iraq on the ground that the
team, which was composed of nine Americans, five Britons, one
Australian and one Russian, lacked balance in its
composition. 
