<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Number of Early Bronze Pieces Unearthed In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 300 pieces of bronzeware
dating back 2,500 years have been uncovered at a sacrificial site
in central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
The site, which was one of China's Top Ten Archaeological Finds
of 1997, is at a construction site in the city of Xinzheng, to the
southwest of the capital of the Zheng State of the Spring and
Autumn Period (770-476 BC).
</P>
<P>
Scholars who selected the top ten finds say that the site was
where the Earl of Zheng, the ruler of the state, held ancestral
and harvest rites.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen pits of bronze pieces and 39 pits of horses buried
alive were found at the site, and 334 pieces of bronzeware
unearthed. These include nine tripod vessels and eight food
containers in one pit and a set of chimes in another.
</P>
<P>
Records show that the number of tripod vessels and food
containers used in sacrificial sites or as burial articles
indicate the rank of the person buried. The highest rank, that of
emperors, is indicated by nine tripod vessels and eight food
containers.
</P>
<P>
The Earl of Zheng defied the rules, scholars say, and that such
cases of defiance were frequent in the Spring and Autumn Period.
</P>
<P>
The set of chimes composed of 24 bronze bells, they say, had
been tuned before being buried, suggesting that they had been
played in a rite just before being buried.
</P>
<P>
The other nine top archaeological finds were: 30,000 pieces of
stoneware in a cave dating back 360,000 years in the Qinglin
Mountains, 7,700-year-old building remains in Shandong province, a
5,000-year-old shell mound site in the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region, the world's oldest paddyfield in Hunan province, a
neolithic site in Hong Kong, the earliest city with imperial
palaces in Henan, the remains of an imperial summer resort of the
Qin Dynasty (221-205 BC), a 2,000-year-old stone structure in
Guangdong, and some 100 ancient tombs on the Silk Road.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
