<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Meets on Cambodian Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ASEAN Troika said in the statement that it welcomed the
separate and unilateral cease-fire declarations by the conflicting
forces in Cambodia and expressed the hope that the forces involved
would exercise restraint and resolve their basic differences so
that the truce may continue to hold.
</P>
<P>
It noted the swift trial of Prince Ranarridh concluded on March
4 and expressed the hope that the second trial of the prince could
be completed at the earliest possible date to allow the early
return of Ranarridh to enable him to meet the deadline for
registration, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Troika also expressed the hope that the return of
Cambodia of King Norodom Sihanouk this April would promote the
cause of national reconciliation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Troika said they are planning to send a special envoy
to pay a visit to Sihanouk in Beijing to "obtain the King's
position on the modality of amnesty for Prince Ranariddh."
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Troika's special envoy to Cambodia, Philippine
Undersecretary of Foreign Affairs for Policy Lauro Baja will visit
Phnom Penh on March 10 to personally brief the Cambodian
government of the results of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the Friends of Cambodia also urged the
Cambodian government to accelerate the process to allow Ranariddh
and other exiled Cambodian political figures to return to
participate in the July elections.
</P>
<P>
"The 'Friends' stressed their wish that this process should be
completed by the time of their next meeting," the Friends of
Cambodia said in a communique released after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN Troika, created during the ASEAN Foreign Ministers
Meeting in Kuala Lumpur last year, and the Friends of Cambodia
agreed to meet again in Bangkok on April 10.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia was supposed to join ASEAN in July 1997 but its entry
was deferred due to political instability in the country. The
ASEAN is composed of Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand, Laos, Vietnam and Myanmar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
