<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators from Ethnic Minorities Confident in Future Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese lawmakers representing
ethnic minorities said they are full of confidence in good
prospects of economic and social development for their ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers, who are here attending the ongoing session of
the Ninth National People's Congress to which they are deputies,
agreed that, since implementation of reform and open policies
began two decades ago, especially in the past five years, regions
with a concentration of ethnic minority people in China have
witnessed tremendous economic growth and social advancement.
</P>
<P>
Huanjue Cenam, a Tibetan deputy from northwest China's Qinghai
Province, described the past five years as "the best period since
the founding of New China" in 1949.
</P>
<P>
"Achievements in these years have proved the great success of
China in combining advantages of the socialist system with a
market economy," said Cenam.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Bao Yizhi, the sole representative of the Tu ethnic
group in the Ninth NPC, expressed appreciation for the importance
Premier Li Peng attached to ethnic minority regions in his
government work report he delivered earlier at the current
session.
</P>
<P>
"This shows the central government's great concern for ethnic
minorities, making us all the more confident in the future," said
Bao, vice mayor of Xining, capital of Qinghai.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the early 1990s, the Tu ethnic people, who
used to stress agriculture and despise commerce, have begun to
accept the concept of market economics and have seen a constant
rise in their living standard.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Deng Bentai, Party secretary of the Golog Tibetan
Autonomous Prefecture in Qinghai, said that his hometown, a
secluded place with extremely harsh natural conditions and
backward economy, last year scored a record 9.96 percent growth
for local Gross Domestic Product with state support.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, the prefectural government in 1997 spent 15
million yuan (nearly two million US dollars) in assisting more
than 9,000 local herdsmen to shake off poverty.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of their expectations, most legislators from ethnic
minorities expressed the hope that the central government would
provide more preferential policies for ethnic minority regions and
inject more investment in comparatively underdeveloped central and
western regions in key sectors like communications and energy
development.
</P>
<P>
China has a total of 55 ethnic minorities, which account for
about four percent of its total population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
