<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar lost half a
U.S. cent to close weaker Friday in Sydney, pressured by lower
Asian regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed here at 66.76 U.S. cents from 67.32
U.S. cents on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brent Aggar, a foreign exchange expert with Macquarie Bank,
said the Australian dollar had been under pressure all day.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian regional currencies are substantially weaker, the
Indonesian rupiah, the Malaysian ringgit and the Singapore dollar
were all, over the week, on a closing basis very much weaker and
that's weighed heavily on the Aussie dollar," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aggar said the low for the day was around 66.5 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
"We could squeeze back to 67.20 U.S. cents but I think the
market will be quiet. If London can't take the Aussie back down
through 66.45 U.S. cents to 66.50 I think we will see a squeeze in
New York up to 67.20 U.S. cents."
</P>
<P>
The focus in the New York markets would be on gold prices
rather than the Asian regional currencies, Aggar said.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar fell to 84.03 yen
from 85.65 at the close in Sydney Thursday. It rose to 1.2228
marks from 1.2217. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
