<HEADLINE> Microsoft Sues Five California Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp. said Thursday
that it is suing five California companies for copyright and
trademark infringement and distribution of alleged counterfeit
products.
</P>
<P>
The companies that allegedly sold or distributed counterfeit
versions of the Windows(R) 95 operating systems, Office 97
Professional Edition and Windows NT(R) Server Operating system are
-- Advanced Digital solutions International Inc., CHL Microsystems
Inc., Gogate International Inc., Silicon Computers as well as
Meladi Electronics Inc, which are all in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
Based on a federal law passed in 1996, Microsoft, the worldwide
leader in software for personal computers, is seeking up to one
million U.S. dollars in damages for each trademark counterfeited.
</P>
<P>
The software industry is a significant driving force of the
current economic prosperity in the United States, making a
102.8-billion-dollar market for software and software-related
services, payment of 7.2 billion dollars in taxes and 619,400 jobs.
</P>
<P>
However, software piracy threatens the ability of the industry
to continue to contribute to the American economy, according to a
1997 study by the Business Software Alliance. The study found that
software piracy in 1996 resulted in the loss of 130,000 jobs,
nearly one billion dollars in tax revenues and 5.3 billion dollars
in wages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
