<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Wool Prices Remain Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Australian Wool prices edged up
slightly at sales this week, although still down on the gains of
last year.
</P>
<P>
"The market appears to have established a new price basis
around 426 U.S. cents a clean kilogram benchmark, which is
bordering on a 10 percent reduction from 1997 price levels," the
Australian Council of Wool Exporters said in its weekly wool
market report.
</P>
<P>
The eastern market indicator rose 1.3 U.S. cents to close at
426 U.S. cents per kg.
</P>
<P>
The western marker indicator remained at 392 U.S. cents per kg
as there were no sales in western Australia's city of Fremantle
and the Australian Wool Exchange's national indicator gained 0.66
U.S. cent to finish at 440 U.S. cents per kg.
</P>
<P>
A total of 58,741 bales were offered at the sales in Sydney and
south Australian coastal city of Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
The council said there was increasing speculation about the
amount of wool likely to be available in the remaining weeks of
the season.
</P>
<P>
"Growers are withholding clips from sale in the wake of the
price drop experienced in January and we will, for example, have
only two auction sales in southern markets over the next six
weeks, including the traditional two week break over Easter.
</P>
<P>
About 79,000 bales will be offered at sales next week in
Sydney, Melbourne and Fremantle.
</P>
<P>
In its weekly report, wool broker Wesfarmers Dalgety said the
firm market marked the fourth consecutive week of stable prices.
</P>
<P>
"The outlook is for the market to remain stable due to the lack
of quantity, with the possibility of an improvement in prices,"
Wesfarmers Dalgety said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
