<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Crisis Blamed for Weak Global Chip Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The economic crisis in Asia
has hurt the growth of the global semiconductor market,
executives at Texas Instruments Inc. said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vladi Catto, chief economist at Texas Instruments, said that
the market would have grown between 15 percent and 17 percent this
year if not for the Asia crisis.
</P>
<P>
That means the global chip market will grow only about 13.5
billion U.S. dollars this year instead of between 20 billion and
23 billion dollars, said the executive.
</P>
<P>
The Asia crisis has taken at least a 6.5-billion-dollar bite
out of the global chip market, he added.
</P>
<P>
He spoke a day after Intel Corp., the world's leading computer
chips maker, stunned Wall Street with a warning of a first-quarter
earnings shortfall, citing weaker-than-anticipated demand for its
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
Weak chip orders "across the board" at the end of 1997 were
pressuring some key markets, said Bill Aylesworth, chief financial
officer at Taxas Instruments.
</P>
<P>
Both executives said the crisis will continue to hurt near-term
profits.
</P>
<P>
They painted a bright picture for 1999, however, saying that
renewed economic growth in Asia would boost demand and help a
recovery in the prices of common memory chips. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
