<HEADLINE> East China Province Standardizing Economic Development Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 6 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province has
recently begun to take measures to regulate its economic
development zones in an effort to encourage overseas investments in
the province.
</P>
<P>
Priority is being given to hi-tech and export-oriented projects
and to the finance, trade, and real estate sectors. Investors will
not be allowed to back projects that use outmoded technology or
equipment or that pollute the environment.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises in the zones are also encouraged to set up bonded
factories, workshops, and warehouses.
</P>
<P>
The number of overseas-funded projects in local development
zones increased to 1,400 last year, accounting for nearly 25
percent of the total in the province.
</P>
<P>
The development zones used 917 million US dollars of overseas
investment in 1997, a nearly 40 percent rise from the 1996 figure.
Their enterprises generated more than 47 billion yuan in
industrial output value in 1997 and earned nearly 1.69 billion US
dollars in foreign exchange from exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
