<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People With Deformities Encouraged in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A young man in east China's
Zhejiang Province recently received 1,000 yuan from the local
government because of his painstaking efforts to deal with his
deformity.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old man, Li Lingqin, who lost a leg in an accident
10 years ago in the city of Ningbo, became reticent, timid, and
afraid of the looks of other people after that.
</P>
<P>
But, with encouragement from the district government, he began
to study harder and eventually passed the Adult Self-teaching
Examination, which gave him further courage.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's policy is to give assistance to people
with deformities, and companies that hire a certain number of them
are entitled to certain preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
The city government of Ningbo has managed to establish a kind
of environment that helps people with deformities build confidence
and to rely on themselves.
</P>
<P>
In addition to encouraging companies to provide jobs, the city
government also provides preferential policies for people with
deformities who want to be self-employed or work in collective
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"People with deformities long for respect rather than
compassion, and only want an equal chance rather than hand-outs,"
Li explains.
</P>
<P>
An official with the city government says that the government
provides various professional training courses for these people to
give them a competitive edge, because "People with deformities
also like fair competition, which provides them with the sense of
equality." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
