<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Deputies Expecting Closer Cross-Strait Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Lawmakers from Fujian, chief
ancestral home of Taiwan compatriots, said they will do what they
can to contribute more to China's peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
In a group discussion on the government work report given by Li
Peng, premier of the State Council, deputies to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), in session here since yesterday,
discussed cross-Strait relations and ways to advance them for an
early reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Li Jiabao, a standing committee member of the Central
Committee of Jiusan Society, one of the eight non-Communist
parties in China, said the Taiwan question is looming larger as
the day is drawing near for Macao's return to the embrace of the
motherland following the successful return of Hong Kong last July.
</P>
<P>
Facing Taiwan across the strait of the same name, Fujian has
the responsibility to promote the reunification of the motherland,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"The urgent thing for Fujian to do now is to accelerate its
opening to the outside world, speed up its economic development
and build up a vibrant economic corridor along the west coast of
the Taiwan Strait," he said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Huang Changxi, a former vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of Fujian Provincial People's Congress, said that over
5,000 Taiwan-funded enterprises have been established along the
highway linking Fuzhou and Xiamen and that tens of thousands of
Taiwan businessmen are now living in the Xiamen-Quanzhou-Fuzhou
area.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the central authorities provide Fujian
with more preferential policies relating to cross-Strait
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to deepen mutual understanding," he said. "One
way of doing this, for example, is to allow more Taiwan students
to study in the mainland." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
