<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Province Vows to Expand Cooperation With EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province in northeast
China, the country's oldest heavy industrial base, plans to improve
its ties with western European countries through a number of
environmental protection projects with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Wen Shizhen, governor of Liaoning, said in an interview with
Xinhua that the projects are not only conducive to sustainable
economic growth but also important to enhancing the mutual
understanding between EU members and the province in its bid to
tap the potential in other fields.
</P>
<P>
So far, the EU has donated 37 million ECU (European Currency
Unit) in carrying out the projects including the use of rivers as
energy sources and the treatment of air pollution and industrial
waste as well as readjusting its industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is home to one-tenth of China's large- and medium-sized
state-owned enterprises with a combined asset value of 500 billion
yuan. The central government has attached great importance to its
reform of traditional companies that are of great appeal to EU
members who bear a lot of similarities with Liaoning in
traditional industrial structure.
</P>
<P>
Wen's recent visit to EU countries has prompted the signing of
a number of contracts as well as letters of intent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
