<HEADLINE> North China City Enhances Development of Forest Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Chengde, a city in north
China's Hebei Province, has set up 10 forest parks to improve its
environment.
</P>
<P>
As a famous city with rich ancient relics, the city is
surrounded by about 8 million hectares of forests.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Chengde took measures to tap its forest
resources and set up three state forest parks at Xingchui Peak,
Mulanweichang and Wulingshan Mountain as well as seven provincial
forest parks.
</P>
<P>
The total area devoted to forest parks is 200,000 hectares with
the Mulanweichang Forest Park being the largest, taking up more
than 60,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Chengde also increased investment in some forest parks for
developing tourist facilities including building skiing
facilities, hunting areas and wild animal parks.
</P>
<P>
The development of forest parks has also boosted tourism in the
city. Last year, more than 2 million overseas and domestic
tourists visited the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
