<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Noted Economists on Enterprise Listing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Three leading Chinese economists
today urged the government to tighten controls over the listing of
enterprises on the country's fledgling stock market to protect
investors' interests and the market itself.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Zhuoji, Liu Hongru and Wu Jinglian, all members of the
Ninth National Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC), China's top advisory body, made
the suggestion in a group discussion attending by members from
the country's economic circles.
</P>
<P>
"The government must take effective steps to strictly regulate
the listing of enterprises and prevent any disqualified enterprise
from getting into the stock market," said Xiao, a professor with
the prestigious Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
He noted that there are now more than 740 listed companies with
a market capitalization of about 1.7 trillion yuan (200 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
"However, some local governments have neglected the quality of
listed companies and even allowed some poorly-managed enterprises
to be listed, affecting the normal operation of the capital
market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Wu, a research fellow with the Development Research Center of
the State Council, China's cabinet, said that the government must
help enterprises change the misconception that the only purpose of
stock listing is to obtain money.
</P>
<P>
"The primary role of the stock market is to realize a rational
capital distribution and promote a needed change in the
operational mechanism of enterprises. Fund-raising is just a
secondary function of the market," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Xiao added that the government must strictly regulate listed
companies and raise their transparency to guarantee an orderly
development of the capital market.
</P>
<P>
Liu, vice president of the Chinese Monetary Society, said that,
as the number of listed companies surges in China, measures must
be taken to ensure their quality.
</P>
<P>
"The quality of listed companies has a direct bearing on the
interests of investors and serves as a cornerstone of the stock
market," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
