<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Capable of Handling Complex Economic Situation: Vice-Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China has made great progress in
economic restructuring and dealt successfully with problems of a
bubble economy in the past five years, demonstrating that the
Chinese government is capable of handling complicated situations
in the process of economic development, said Wu Bangguo, a
vice-premier of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the comment in a group discussion attended by deputies
to the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC) in session here
since yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Wu said the last five years are one of the best periods since
the founding of New China in terms of national economic
development. He enumerated reasons for his comment: the country
has had a rational foreign debt structure; it has embarked on a
road of economic development featuring a high speed and low
inflation; and it has maintained financial stability and good
growth momentum at a time when Southeast Asia is plagued by
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"China's steady, fast and healthy economic growth and stable
financial order are a positive factor for Asia's economic
stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since China implemented policies of reform and opening to the
outside world, he said, links between the country's domestic
market and international markets have become closer.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis in Southeast Asia is expected to have some
impact on China's export and economic development, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is an arduous task for China to maintain the current
economic growth momentum, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wu called for working hard to expand both the domestic and
international markets and directing more investment in
agriculture, forestry, infrastructure, new and high-tech
technologies, technological upgrading and residential housing
construction.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that China can achieve an eight-percent
economic growth rate while bring inflation under three percent in
1998 as long as the government handles macro controls well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
