<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rebound on Postal Savings Funds Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices in Tokyo rebounded Friday,
pulled up by a higher futures index on news reports that the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) is considering injecting postal savings
funds to boost stock prices.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section of
the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 283.42 points, or 1.68 percent, from
Thursday's close to 17,131.97.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, advanced 11.69 points, or 0.92 percent,
to 1,287.95.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the section came to an estimated 400 million shares,
almost unchanged from Thursday's 398.23 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Friday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
After three days of losses, share prices rebounded on a news report
Friday that 1 trillion yen (about 7.9 billion dollars) worth of
postal savings and insurance funds could be pumped into the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,330 issues listed on the First Section, gainers outpaced
losers 741 to 341 with 162 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
