<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold And Silver Products Doing Well In Chinese Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- You'd be wrong if you tried to
buy mutton at the Yangrou (mutton) Hutong in the Western District
of Beijing -- try buying gold instead, because shops selling gold
and silver trinkets have replaced a number of old shops along the
narrow street.
</P>
<P>
The hutong was designated a special gold and silver market by
the Geology and Mineral Resources Ministry and the Western
District government in 1994, in response to consumer needs.
</P>
<P>
It now has 43 gold and silver jewelry shops, each with annual
sales of about a million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all of Beijing's large department stores have opened
special counters here and have monthly sales of about a million
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Beijing now has six centers for gold, silver, and pearl objects
and many other wholesale markets and special shops. Sales for 1997
amounted to several billion yuan in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The prosperous gold and silver markets can be explained by the
fact that Beijing is a major distribution center of jewelry, and
there are an increasing number of foreigners coming to the city
and people's incomes are increasing. 
</P>
