<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Old Tomb With Frescoes Discovered in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered a tomb dating back to the Song Dynasty (960 to 1279
A.D.), with frescoes on the chamber walls, in the city of Xinmi in
central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
It was discovered at a building site for a farmer's house, just
underground, at the foot of a bluff in Xinmi, not far away from
Kaifeng, the capital of the Northern Song Dynasty about 1,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
The chambers are made of brick in an octagonal shape. The
vaulted celling is three meters high. The largest brick is 50 cm
long. The frescoes on the walls of the chambers tell of stories of
24 famous dutiful sons, and most are well preserved.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists say the tomb was a copy of the architectural
style of buildings above ground. They plan to do a full-scale
excavation of the tomb, which is believed to contain a number of
funerary items.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
