<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaria Under Control in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- The malaria epidemic that killed at
least 138 people in the southern Philippines has been under
control, the Philippine News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said Mustala Hairon, secretary of Mindanao office of
the Department of Health, said this after making an on-site visit
to Siasi town, Sulu province on the southern island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"With all the help that is pouring into Siasi and all the
efforts given, the epidemic is contained. Health personnel had
done malaria control measures even in neighboring islands to stop
its spread," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, most victims were suffering from malnutrition and lack
of water supply and their ability to fight off epidemic diseases
had been reduced, Hairon added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, He belied reports that health personnel were late in
responding to the incident.
</P>
<P>
He said Sulu Provincial Health Office had sent doctors to Siasi
as early as February 20 when the malaria first broke out.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Fidel Ramos announced Siasi a calamity area
and released millions of pesos as emergency assistance to the
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
