<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Creates "Heroes Street" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- On busy Chaowai Avenue in east
Beijing stand 50 huge, round, mirror-like light boxes on both
sides of the street bearing pictures of Chinese heroes.
</P>
<P>
The avenue, 1,080 meters in length and the location of such
famous buildings as the Ministry of Foreign Affairs Office
Building and the Blue-Island Building, now has a new nickname --
Beijing's "Heroes Street."
</P>
<P>
"These pictures make me feel that heroes are not actually far
away from us; they are just among the public," said a young man on
his bicycle, who goes to and from work past the pictures.
</P>
<P>
According to an official with the Chaoyang District which
sponsored the pictures late last year, their purpose is to
publicize the heroes' noble spirit of devotion to the liberation
and development of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"We will keep these light-boxes standing on the street-sides
forever so the passers-by have the opportunity to commemorate our
national heroes every day and be nurtured by their spirit of
patriotism," the official said.
</P>
<P>
These 50 heroes include Lei Feng, a model soldier who always
tried to help others; Meng Tai, a model worker who tried to save
every cent for his factory; and Wu Jinyin, a good Party chief at
the grassroot level who worked hard to help villagers rise from
poverty.
</P>
<P>
"These 50 heroes were selected from more than 100 candidates by
both the public and experts," said the official, adding that some
worthy people had to be omitted because of the lack of good
pictures.
</P>
<P>
The street also provides an ideal place for primary school
students to learn from former generations.
</P>
<P>
"Every time I pass by the pictures of Dong Cunrui and Huang
Jiguang (who have been widely known by the Chinese for protecting
their comrades with their own lives during wartime), I will more
cherish the peace and happy life I have today," said one student
from the Fangcaodi Primary School in the Chaoyang District.
</P>
<P>
In front of the District Government Building stand two huge
light-boxes with pictures of Kong Fansen and Li Suli (who are
known as model civil servants).
</P>
<P>
"This is to remind the government officials of serving the
people better," a passer-by told Xinhua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
