<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Curbing Fraud Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 6 (Xinhua) -- There is need for the
establishment of a multi-sectoral and specialised committee to
assist with investigations of all forms of serious fraud if the
crime is to be controlled, a Zimbabwean minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a two-day conference on "winning the war against
corporate fraud" on Thursday in Harare, minister of home affair
Dumiso Dabengwa said that at least 80 cases of fraud are recorded
every week in Zimbabwe, the daily The Herald reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"From these statistics," he said, "it is clear that fraud is
costing the country losses running into millions of dollars every
year," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said these losses were suffered by the private citizens,
government departments, non-governmental organisations,
parastatals and private concerns -- both big and small.
</P>
<P>
The minister said criminals were becoming so sophisticated
that traditional investigation methods were failing to cope,
hence the need for the setting up of a specialised agency to help
curb the crime.
</P>
<P>
"The committee should include experienced senior police
officers, lawyers, loss-control officers from the banking
industry and financial institutions, accountants, and computer
specialists among other experts," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed corporate fraud was a major concern to both the
government and affected organisations in that it caused "severe
bleeding" of the economy.
</P>
<P>
At the same occasion, police deputy commissioner Dave Blake
said police were doing all they could to investigate all forms of
fraud, but this was not enough deterrent.
</P>
<P>
He said a total of 6,122 cases were reported in 1997, an
increase of 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the police would go out of their way to fight the
fraud menace which had engulfed Zimbabwe. He also urged the
participants to set up a committee to come up with a competency
framework strategy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
