<HEADLINE> Exim Bank Provides Insurance Bill for Thai Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's exporters will be able
to obtain an additional 116 billion baht (2.6 billion US dollars)
in liquidity through the Export-Import (Exim) Bank 's new trade
bill insurance program and direct lending of packing credits,
Bangkok Post newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Exim's President Pridiyathorn Devakula as
saying that the bank will have four new facilities available to
exporters next month, giving access to funds at interest rates
lower than those available on the market.
</P>
<P>
The programs are yen and US dollar-denominated credit
facilities, baht direct credits, insurance for export bills and
financing support for raw material imports.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Bank of Thailand, the central bank, will also
provide about five billion baht (111 million dollars) in liquidity
support by mid-March, supplemented by the Exim Bank.
</P>
<P>
Also, the central bank has approved a change in the risk weight
assigned to letters of credit and trade bills for commercial
banks, from 100 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
All these are part of the government's move to boost export,
which bears the hope of the country's economic recovery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
