<HEADLINE> China to Continue Expanding Telephone Service 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- One out of every 10 Chinese people
will share a telephone set by the end of 1998, according to the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has set a goal of increasing the total number of
telephone users to the equivalent of 9.7 percent of the population
this year. In urban areas, 30 percent of the population will have
telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had 83.5 million telephone users. It
has the second largest telephone network in the world. This year
the number of telephone users will grow by 20 million to more than
100 million.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 million of those users will have mobile
telephones, marking an increase of eight million over 1997. China
had become the third largest user of mobile telephones in the
world by the end of last year, with 13.23 million people having a
mobile telephone.
</P>
<P>
China will also accelerate the expansion of digital
telecommunications this year. The number of end users of digital
telecommunications and multi-media is expected to grow by 400,000
this year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had 360,000 users of digital
telecommunications. The number of Internet users in China
quadrupled to 160,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
The country will complete a nationwide optical cable network
with 16 trunk cable lines extending from north to south and from
east to west.
</P>
<P>
The volume of business transactions of the posts and
telecommunications industry is expected to grow by 28 percent this
year over 1997. The volume was 177.9 billion yuan (21.4 billion
U.S. dollars) for 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
