<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Appeals to Solve Kosovo Crisis Through Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's Foreign Ministry has
called for all-party talks to find a solution to the deepening
crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian Telegraph Agency reported Thursday that Bulgaria
was seriously worried that the violence between Serbian
authorities and ethnic Albanians could spread beyond Kosovo to
other regions.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, which borders Yugoslavia, appealed to all parties to
start constructive talks to prevent the crisis threatening the
security of the region, the ministry was reported as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government believed that other countries in the region should
unite to avoid further conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The visiting NATO commander of forces southern Europe,
Joseph Lopez, said Thursday, that NATO hoped to find a peaceful
solution to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 people died the same day in a clash in the Srbica
region, about 30 kilometers west of the province's capital,
Pristina, according to the Yugoslavian news agency Tanjug
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Kosovo escalated on March 1 when four policemen and
16 Albanians died in an armed battle.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians, who account for 90 percent of the population,
have been seeking independence from Yugoslavia since 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
