<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Defense Official: Dialogue Leads to Greater </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- A Senior U.S. defense official
said here Thursday that the Pentagon is seeking more dialogue with
the Chinese military to promote mutual understanding and reduce
miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth H. Bacon, assistant secretary of defense for public
affairs and the Pentagon's chief spokesperson, told reporters that
"the more that China and the U.S. can talk to each other, the more
avenues we have open between us, I think the better and sounder
our relationships will be, the better our understanding will be."
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. military have been engaged in "types of
discussions and openness" with their Chinese counterparts since
Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian visited Washington in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that that dialogue leads to a greater
understanding. And understanding reduces the chances of
miscalculation. It reduces the chances of people making mistakes
in their dealings with one another," Bacon noted.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen returned a visit to
China early this year. The trip has led to the signing of an
accord on avoiding accidents in the sea.
</P>
<P>
Bacon admitted that differences still exist between the two
sides, but they could be overcome through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"We understand that we are not going to agree with everything
China does, nor is China going to agree with every part of our
policy. That's a given between any two sovereign nations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to develop, despite our differences, ways to
overcome those differences and work around them and to cooperate
in areas that make sense to us and where we can make the world
stable, and in areas where we may disagree, to disagree in a
mature and non-disruptive way," Bacon added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
