<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav President, British FM Hold Talk on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic said Thursday that his government will try to
seek a political solution to the ethnic Albanian unrest in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic made the remark in a meeting with visiting British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, the Tanjug news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, two Serbian policemen and 20 ethnic Albanians
were killed in the latest outbreak of violence.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic said that Yugoslavia will take all measures to
eradicate terrorism in the province, but a division should be
made between the terrorists and mainstream ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Violence erupted on March 1 when Serbian police and Albanians
clashed, leaving four policemen and 16 Albanians dead.
</P>
<P>
The president also called on Britain, currently chairing the
European Union presidency, to help develop cooperation between
Yugoslavia and the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who arrived in Belgrade Wednesday, also called for a
political solution in Kosovo where ethnic Albanians, who make up
90 percent of the population, have been seeking independence since
1981.
</P>
<P>
He condemned terrorism, but stressed that the problems
could not be solved by force.
</P>
<P>
Cook also met Yugoslav Foreign Minister Zivadin Jovanovic. He
called on the government to allow the establishment of an EU
office in Kosovo to monitor the situation and before decisions
were made on EU economic aid to the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
