<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina's Yacimientos Petroliferos Fiscales
state oil firm earned profits of 877 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The company announced that it paid 473 million dollars in
income tax and nine million dollars in dividends on preferential
shares.
</P>
<P>
It said that at the end of 1997 its capital amounted to 4.691
billion dollars while its net assets reached 6.94 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Mergers and acquisitions of companies by foreign
firms in Chile were valued at 4.049 billion dollars in 1997, a
15.8 percent drop on 1996, the Santiago Chamber of Commerce said.
</P>
<P>
The energy sector was the main area of interest, with
operations amounting to 2.248 billion dollars, followed by
services at 704 million dollars and mining at 287 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The countries investing the most in Chile were Spain at 37.6
percent, followed by Argentina at 8.2 percent, Japan at 6.3
percent, Britain at 4.6 percent, and the United States at four
percent.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's earnings from oil exports fell by 560
million dollars in January because of price decreases in the
international market, reported the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Venezuelan oil exports amounted to 910 million dollars in
January.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices started falling at the end of December and worsened
at the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile made 2,233 automobiles in January, including
1,890 pickup trucks and 343 cars, the Motor Vehicle Commission of
the Development Corporation said.
</P>
<P>
It said 85 percent of the automobiles are Chevrolets.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The World Bank will grant 30 million dollars to
Central America this year for social projects, said Bank president
James Wolfensohn.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank was trying to improve living standards in
Central American countries with economic development, said
Wolfensohn, who arrived in Nicaragua on Wednesday as part of a
tour of six Central American countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
