<HEADLINE> Singapore Firm to Add More CDMA Phones in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 6 (Xinhua) -- A Singapore firm has agreed with
Myanmar to add 20,000 more CDMA mobile phones in Yangon, the
country's capital, to boost the city's local and international
direct dialing capacity.
</P>
<P>
Under a contract signed here Thursday between Singapore's Ucom
International and state-run Myanmar Posts and Telecommunications,
the Singaporean company will supply CDMA equipment manufactured by
Qualcomm Inc of the United States, The New Light of Myanmar
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Some 3,000 CDMA phones have been under installation since last
October according to an earlier contract reached in August 1996.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the CDMA telephone system in Yangon
followed the extensive use of cellular phones in the capital.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, foreign companies involved in
the installation of new telephone systems in Myanmar in recent
years include those from Australia, Israel, Germany, Japan,
Singapore and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that the country's telecommunications
sector achieved a 20.6 percent growth in the gross domestic
product in the 1996-97 fiscal year against the target of 9
percent. The growth target for the current 1997-98 fiscal year
ending March was set at 7.9 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
