<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Cut Deficit by 10 Billion Yuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to have a
deficit of 46 billion yuan this year, 10 billion yuan less than
last year's actual deficit, China's Finance Minister Liu Zhongli
said here today, addressing the annual session of the National
People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
This will be the biggest drop in China's recent budgets.
</P>
<P>
After being faced with a deficit of 65.68 billion yuan in 1995,
the central government has been striving to basically balance its
budget by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Last year, central expenditures exceeded revenues, leaving a
deficit of 56 billion yuan, one billion yuan less than the
budgeted amount, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to efforts to deepen reform, strengthen management, and
effectively implement an appropriately stringent financial policy
in the past few years, the country's financial situation is
improving, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Total state revenue for 1997 increased by 123.4 billion yuan
over the 1996 figure. The proportion of individual income tax,
stamp tax on securities transactions and business tax in the total
revenue increased from 15.1 percent in 1994 to 21 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This shows that with restructuring of the national economy,
sources for revenue increases have diversified to create favorable
conditions for sustained and steady growth in revenue, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, total expenditures were brought under control. The
increase in expenditures for 1997 was lower than the increase in
revenue.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, newly added expenditures were used for
substantial increases in investment in education, science, risk
funds for grain production, anti-poverty funds and building up the
national strength, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will continue to implement an appropriately stringent
financial policy, oppose the unhealthy practices of squandering
public funds and indulging in extravagance and waste, streamline
the administrative structure and reduce the number of personnel
supported by the state finance and spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
