<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imelda Gets Temporary Reprieve from Supreme Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Philippine First Lady Imelda
Marcos has gotten a temporary reprieve from her 12-year conviction
for graft after a Supreme Court division suggested a review of her
case by the entire tribunal.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star reported on Friday that the tribunal's
third division referred the matter to the entire court as it acted
on a motion filed by Imelda on February 25 to allow a full-court
hearing to review and reverse her conviction.
</P>
<P>
Imelda was sentenced to 12 years in prison by a Manila court in
1993 for underpricing a government-owned lot in Manila to a
private company in 1984. A division of the Supreme Court upheld
the ruling on January 29 this year.
</P>
<P>
In her six-page motion, Imelda said the ruling was only based
on the evidence presented by the prosecution and that was not
enough. She also wanted to know why she was convicted while her
co-accused, former transportation minister Jose Dans, was
acquitted.
</P>
<P>
Once the tribunal accepts Imelda's motion, her scheduled
detention will take a little longer since the case can drag on for
a certain period of time. If not, she might be jailed before the
year-end, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Imelda is a House representative of her hometown Leyte province
at present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
