<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Planning Commission Minister: China to Step Up Reforms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 6 (Xinhua) -- China will strive to accelerate
the establishment of a socialist market economy and continue to
make progress in the reform of major areas this year.
</P>
<P>
These remarks came from Chen Jinhua, minister in charge of the
State Planning Commission, in his report on the implementation of
the 1997 plan for national economic and social development and on
the draft 1998 plan for national economic and social development
to the ongoing First Session of the Ninth National People's
Congress today.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, China will step up the pace of reforms in
the following areas:
</P>
<P>
-- Successfully reforming state enterprises. Aiming mainly at
improving the state sector of the economy as a whole, China will
effectuate a strategic reorganization of state-owned enterprises
through good management of large enterprises while relaxing
control over small ones. The capital reserves added for clearing
bad debts in 1998 will be used mainly to extricate the textile
industry from its difficulties and on major restructuring items.
China will combine financing in the stock market with the reform
of state-owned enterprises and encourage listed companies to merge
with enterprises that have good prospects but are experiencing
temporary difficulties. China will also make the textile industry
the forerunner in the reform of state-owned enterprises and in the
campaign to extricate those enterprises from their difficulties.
The government will begin in the coastal provinces and cities in
1998 and strive to spread successful practices to the interior.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Planning Commission Minister: China to Step Up Reforms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
-- Speeding up reform of the financial system. China plans to
use three years to basically establish financial institutions,
financial markets and a system of financial control and
supervision to gear to a socialist market economy. This should
improve the operation and management of the financial industry and
bring about a marked turn for the better in financial order across
the country. China will put an end to the proportioned
distribution of branches of the People's Bank of China (PBC) and
state-owned commercial banks in all administrative divisions and
reduce the number of management bodies and branches. China will
increase the number of urban commercial banks and start to
experiment with county (city) commercial banks in selected areas.
China will also gradually develop the capital market, expanding
the use of direct financing as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
-- Reforming the grain distribution system. China will
gradually establish a grain distribution system that is suited to
a socialist market economy and able to carry out the state's
macro-control tasks. China will further relax control over and
invigorate the retail market for grain. The government will set
protective prices for purchasing grain and ceiling prices for
selling it, and regulate market supply and demand and prices
mainly through economic means such as the use of its grain
reserves.
</P>
<P>
-- Continuing to deepen the price reform. The mechanism for
setting prices mainly through the market will be improved. The
government will review the temporary administrative measures it
took to control prices in order to curb inflation, and abolish or
revise regulations incompatible with the current economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
-- Improving the macro-control system. Macroeconomic control
and coordination will be further improved. To address the new
conflicts and problems arising in the economic operation, China
will balance economic growth and efficiency, and overall economic
growth and the pattern of growth, and appropriately tighten and
trim monetary policy. The government will mainly guide and
standardize the activities of all major economic entities by
economic and legal means.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Parliament Passes Security Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian Parliament passed the
country's security and defense law with an overwhelming majority
Thursday, with 226 affirmative and 14 negative votes, the
Ukrainian Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The law provides for the Ukrainian State Committee on Security
and Defense to be composed of the country's prime minister,
defense minister, National Security Service director, interior
minister and foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The present members of the committee are Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoitenko, Defense Minister Oleksandr Kuzmuk, National
Security Service Director Vladimir Radchenko, Interior Minister
Yury Kravchenko and Foreign Minister Gennady Vdovenko.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, the country's president, Leonid Kuchma, heads
the committee and has rights to appoint and sack the committee's
secretary. The present secretary is Vladimir Gorbulin.
</P>
<P>
The committee's main functions are to make suggestion on
security and defense policies to the president. It is to
coordinate and supervise the authority on security and defense
work in peace periods, and aid the government if there is imminent
threat to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
