All reported that the First Session of the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC) opened in the Great Hall of the People in
Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng delivered a Government Work Report on behalf of
the State Council, which consists of three parts: government work
over the past five years, suggestions on government work in 1998,
and international situation and China's diplomatic work.
</P>
<P>
A total of 2,944 deputies from 32 provinces, autonomous regions
and centrally-administered municipalities, from the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region and the People's Liberation Army,
attended the opening meeting.
</P>
<P>
The session will elect people for the following posts for new
terms of office: president of the country, chairman of the Central
Military Commission, chairman of the Standing Committee of the the
Ninth NPC, president of the Supreme People's Court, and
procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
On the basis of nominations by the president of the country,
the session will decide on the new premier and members of the
State Council.
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng put forward suggestions for Beijing's
development in a group discussion attended by Beijing deputies to
the NPC.
</P>
<P>
He urged the establishment of more high-tech ventures in
Beijing with the help of Beijing-based scientific institutions and
encouragement of the upgrading of traditional industries.
</P>
<P>
Li also stressed the importance of attaching equal importance
to the sustainable economic growth and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Having their first taste of democracy with Chinese
characteristics, representatives from Hong Kong were both excited
and inspired. "Premier Li Peng's report sang high praise for Hong
Kong. I feel very excited," said Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
-- People expressed high expectations when asked what they
anticipate from the country's top event -- the inauguration of the
Ninth NPC. They said they were eager to know who will be the state
president, legislative leader, premier, and ministers of the new
state ministries and commissions.
</P>
<P>
-- China cautioned other countries to be on guard against
Taiwan authorities' political maneuvers and handle their relations
with Taiwan appropriately. 
</P>
