<HEADLINE> Harkness Denies Collymore Racism Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Liverpool defender Steve Harkness
said in a press release on Thursday that he did not racially abuse
Aston Villa striker Stan Collymore during the team's English
premier league match at Villa Park on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released by Liverpool, Harkness said: "I
vehemently deny the accusation that I made racist comments to Stan
Collymore during or after the game at Aston Villa.
</P>
<P>
"Contrary to press reports, I did not at any point attempt to
enter the Aston Villa dressing room and was not involved in any
scuffle with Stan Collymore.
</P>
<P>
"The particular background to this game may have meant that
there was more going on on the pitch than is usual, but that does
not extend to racial abuse of any kind.
</P>
<P>
"I am not a racist and I am proud to count Paul Ince and his
family as some of my closest friends and people with whom I and my
family spend a lot of time."
</P>
<P>
Liverpool have given their full backing to Harkness and have
asked Professional Footballers' Association representative Brendan
Batson to mediate in the affair.
</P>
<P>
Collymore, who moved from Liverpool to Villa in the summer for
7 million pounds (11.5 million U.S. dollars), claimed Harkness had
abused him during the game that Villa won 2-1.
</P>
<P>
Collymore was quoted in English newspapers as saying:
"Harkness called me a 'coon' and some things even worse. I was
getting racial abuse from him and being wound up throughout the
game.
</P>
<P>
"It is Steve Harkness that has to live with this now. I have
made it my business to make sure the black players at Liverpool
know what was said.
</P>
<P>
"Harkness has got to be part of that squad with those players,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
