- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan will pay an
official visit to the Middle East from March 19 to 26 of this
month, UN spokesman Fred Eckhard announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief originally planned to visit the Middle East in mid
February. But he postponed his visit because of the recent crisis
over the United Nations weapons inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"He will visit Egypt, Israel, Lebanon Syria and the areas under
the jurisdiction of Palestine, " the spokesman said. (Annan-Middle
East-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on Thursday
strongly condemned a bomb blast in Sri Lanka, which killed at
least 28 people.
</P>
<P>
"Once again, the Secretary-General condemns, in the strongest
possible terms the use of violence against civilians," his
spokesman Fred Eckhard told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism cannot be condoned in any circumstances," Annan was
quoted as saying. (UN-Sri Lanka-Bombing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- France Thursday expressed concern over reports from
Yugoslavia that the Yugoslav security forces have launched an
operation against a village of ethnic Albanians in the province of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"If these reports are confirmed, they would attest an
escalation of the violence which went in the opposite direction of
the appeal for restraint by the international community and
France," said French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne
Gazeau-Secret. (France-Yugoslavia-Kosovo) 
</P>
