<HEADLINE> CFO and EU Meet on World Cup Ticket Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 5 (Xinhua) -- World Cup Organising Committee
(CFO) and the European Union officials met on Thursday, discussing
a possible way to settle down a dispute over the allocation of
tickets by France for the competition.
</P>
<P>
World Cup organisers' representatives and lawyers met EU
officials for three hours in Brussels to discuss the matter.
</P>
<P>
CFO director general Jacques Lambert told reporters the meeting
had been constructive, but he declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
A number of European soccer associations, led by England, have
complained about how few tickets they will receive for the
French-organised competition.
</P>
<P>
A final decision on ticket allocation will be made at a meeting
between CFO and world soccer body FIFA in Paris next week.
</P>
<P>
Organisers have claimed they have merely followed guidelines
agreed months ago by FIFA and approved by the EU while the
European Union executive said the current allocation of tickets,
giving 60 percent of all tickets to French residents, could breach
EU anti-trust laws. 
</P>
</TEXT>
