<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Friend Testifies for  Second Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Vernon Jordan, U.S. President
Bill Clinton's close friend, said Thursday he did not help former
White House intern Monica sewinsky find a job and a lawyer in
exchange for her silence.
</P>
<P>
Following his second day of testimony before a federal grand
jury, Jordan reiterated that he never told Lewinsky to lie about
her relationship with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Jordan told reporters, "I did not in any way tell her,
encourage her, to lie. My efforts to help find her a job were not
a quid pro quo for the affidavit that she signed."
</P>
<P>
In her sworn affidavit given to Paula Jones's lawyers, Lewinsky
stated she never had a sexual relationship with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr is investigating whether
President Clinton, or an intermediary, urged Lewinsky to deny the
alleged affair.
</P>
<P>
Jordan maintained he did nothing to influence Lewinsky's
testimony.
</P>
<P>
He said, "That's the truth, that's the whole truth, that's
nothing but the truth."
</P>
<P>
Jordan said he was not certain whether he would be called back
for more testimony, but he told reporters, "I have fought a good
fight, I have finished my course, I have kept the faith, and we
will see what time will tell us."  
</P>
</TEXT>
