<HEADLINE> U.S. Stocks Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Dragged by a fall-off in
Intel-led technology shares, U.S. stocks fell sharply on Thursday,
with the Dow Jones industrial average ending 94.16 points lower to
8,445.08.
</P>
<P>
This was Dow's second biggest decline this year since January 9
when 220 points were lost due to investors' worries about the
impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Intel, world's number one chip-maker, lost almost 13 percent on
the New York Stock Exchange following its announcement last night
that its first quarter earnings may drop 10 percent, citing lower
demand for PCs as a reason.
</P>
<P>
Intel faces fierce competition from other companies for low
priced chips used in sub-1,000 U.S. dollars machines.
</P>
<P>
Share prices of other computer companies followed suit,
pressuring the technology-heavy Nastaq composite index to go down
47.78 to 1,711.92.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock list fell 12.29 to 1,035.04 and
the NYSE composite index fell 4.16 to 540.30.
</P>
<P>
On the smaller companies' line, the Russell 2000 index was down
5.31 to 456.82 and the American Stock Exchange composite index
fell 4.84 to 704.31.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House of Representatives Legislation to Ease Child </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen states in the United
States that have failed to computerize their child support systems
would escape severe penalties under legislation approved by the
House of Representatives on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Although these states would still face fines, they would be a
fraction of what a 1988 law required. The legislation now goes to
the Senate, where some lawmakers support even lower penalties.
</P>
<P>
Under current law, states without working computer systems
would lose all federal child support funding, which is used to run
collection systems. In addition, state welfare funding is
contingent on having a working child support program, and states
could lose their entire block grant.
</P>
<P>
Representative Clay Shaw, co-sponsor of the bill acted on
Thursday, said, "Penalties of this magnitude are devastating and
would cripple both the child support and welfare programs. Then
everyone would lose."
</P>
<P>
His legislation would reduce the penalty to 4 percent of child
support funding for this year, increasing to 8 percent next year
and 16 percent in 2000. States that haven't finished their systems
by 2001 would lose 20 percent each year. They would not lose any
general welfare funding.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, Congress required states to computerize their systems
to allow for easier tracking of parents who owe money as they
travel within a state and between states. Since then, more than
2.6 billion dollars has been spent on the project. The deadline
was extended once to give states until October to finish their
work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Set Agendas for 2nd Summit of Americas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said Thursday that education, free trade,
economic reform and narcotics control will be high on the agenda
of the second summit of Americas to be held in Santiago.
</P>
<P>
"Our leaders will seek to build on the vision of a true
hemisphere community put forward in Miami three years ago,"
Albright told the Organization of American States (OAS).
</P>
<P>
A two-day "Conference of Americas" celebrating the OAS's 50th
anniversary was convened at the organization's headquarters in
Washington as a preparation for the Santiago summit.
</P>
<P>
"Together in Santiago, we should reaffirm our conviction that
the path to increased prosperity for the greatest number resides
not in a retreat from reform, but in its refinement, in more
openness, coupled with more accountability and high standards,"
said Albright.
</P>
<P>
"The discussions in Santiago will also review so-called
second-generation economic reforms that extend accountability and
the rule of law to the financial world, thereby promoting
prosperity that is broad-based and less vulnerable to the kind of
disruptions we see now in East Asia," she added.
</P>
<P>
The second summit of Americas will take place in early April.
President Bill Clinton and leaders from other 33 countries on the
hemisphere will attend the event.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will also seek to launch negotiations to create a
Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA) by the year of 2005,
according to Albright.
</P>
<P>
The secretary stressed that "the FTAA remains a keystone of
the president's policy of cooperation in this hemisphere."
</P>
<P>
The summit will restate commitment to the war against
international narcotics trafficking and crime, she added.
</P>
<P>
"We must move ahead together on all fronts and unite in
emphasizing to the people throughout the region that... drugs are
wrong, drugs are illegal, drugs will kill you," she affirmed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
