<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eileen Collins Named U.S. First Female Shuttle Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Air Force Lt.Col. Eileen
Collins, the first woman to pilot a U.S. space shuttle, was named
the first woman to command a shuttle mission December this year.
</P>
<P>
At a White House ceremony thursday, U.S. President Bill Clinton
said, "Heroes come in all sizes and gender", "even the sky is no
longer the limit".
</P>
<P>
"Today we celebrate the falling away of another barrier in
America's quest to conquer the frontiers of space," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Collins became the first woman to pilot a space shuttle when
she flew aboard a mission in February 1995 that was the first
flight of the new joint Russian-American Space Program. Her second
shuttle flight in May 1997 was the sixth mission to rendezvous and
dock with the Russian space station Mir. She has logged more than
419 hours in space.
</P>
<P>
During her December shuttle Columbia mission, she will command
the shuttle to launch the 1.4 billion Advanced X-ray telescope
that is a counterpart to the orbiting Hubble Space Telescope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
