<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Public Employees Protest Government Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Turkish public sector workers took
to streets Thursday to protest a government-proposed bill which
allegedly aims to limit union rights.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale demonstrations were reported in the provinces of
Ankara, Istanbul, Antalya, Edirne, Gaziantep as well as Samsun,
according to the Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of protesters gathered in downtown Ankara to show
their anger over the new union bill, saying that they were
determined to defend their legal rights and freedom.
</P>
<P>
They shouted slogans such as "We are right, we'll win," and
"No to fake union laws."
</P>
<P>
Protesters clashed with riot police armed with batons and gas
grenades. Some people were wounded.
</P>
<P>
They said Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and Deputy Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit, who earlier enjoyed wide support from
public workers, want to limit the rights of the labor unions.
</P>
<P>
Cengiz Uzuner, a senior member of the KESK, said that railway,
postal and health workers all participated in the nationwide
strike aimed at defending civil rights.
</P>
<P>
"Work has halted all around the country. We will continue our
protest until the government withdraws this bill," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's demonstration in the central district of the
capital was a continuation of Wednesday evening's protest on the
same spot in which about 7,000 labor union members were involved.
</P>
<P>
Local televisions were constantly showing the scenes that many
protesters sitting on the ground shivered under the freezing water
spurted by police water cannons.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-eight protesters and 21 policemen wounded in the clashes
were rushed to the hospitals for treatment.
</P>
<P>
On the public sector protests around the country, Yilmaz said
that the demonstration took place at a "wrong time," saying this
will do no good to the issue.
</P>
<P>
"If everyone takes to the streets to protest a bill currently
being discussed in Parliament, this means inflicting pressure on
Parliament, and therefore it may have a negative effect on
Parliament's work," he said.
</P>
<P>
The controversial bill submitted by the Yilmaz government last
month is now still under the Parliament debate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
