<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Grants for Community Oriented Policing Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
Thursday announced more than 31 million dollars in new Community
Oriented Policing Services (COPS) grants to help put 500 new
police officers and sheriff's deputies on the rolls of 186
agencies nationwide.
</P>
<P>
The COPS, part of the 1994 Crime Act, aims at adding 100,000
officers to the nation's streets by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore made the announcement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Since the passage of the Crime Act, COPS funds have helped more
than 10,000 agencies put more than 71,000 officers on the streets.
COPS provides 75 percent of the salary and benefits for each
officer up to three years, for a maximum of 75,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the communities receiving larger grants in the latest
round of funding are Orleans Parish in Louisiana, Richland County
in South Carolina, Desert Springs in California, Conway in
Arkansas, and Port Lucie in Florida. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
