<HEADLINE> Britain to Host Meeting on Iraq Food-for-Oil Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook announced Thursday evening that Britain is to host an
international conference on implementing a new U.N. deal to
increase the amount of oil Iraq can sell for food.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a London conference on the Middle East, Cook said
that Britain, as the current European Union (EU) president, will
organize a meeting to work out how Europe and others can help the
U.N. in swift and effective implementation of the expanded
oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
"Doubling the size of the program throws up many opportunities
which we are determined to seize" in an effort to meet the most
pressing needs of the Iraqi people, Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Cook noted that the planned meeting "will provide a chance to
consult with all the key players, including the U.N. and NGOs (non
governmental organizations), to ensure that the European
contribution to the scheme is used to the fullest advantage of the
Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary did not give the concrete date for the
conference, but British government officials reportedly said that
the meeting will take place before the end of June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
