<DOCNO> XIE19980306.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Withdraws Offer for Yugoslavia over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States on Thursday
decided to punish Yugoslavia for escalating violence in Kosovo by
withdrawing limited economic concessions granted only last week to
lift sanctions.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley warned that there will
be "serious negative consequences" for the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia as a result of the latest violence in the Kosovo
province.
</P>
<P>
The United States is withdrawing positive measures announced by
U.S. Bosnia special envoy Robert Gelbard when visiting Belgrade
last week, said Foley.
</P>
<P>
The measures are mainly cosmetic because Washington has
insisted on maintaining the so-called "outer-wall" of sanctions,
imposed by the U.S. and its allies in 1992 when the former
Yugoslavia broke up.
</P>
<P>
Foley confirmed that four measures withdrawn include Belgrade's
participation in the U.S. Southern Europe Cooperation Initiative,
a plan to increase number of Yugoslavia's diplomats in New York at
the U.N., opening a consulate in the U.S., landing rights for
Yugoslav airline in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Foley threatened that the U.S. will respond further to possible
actions taken by Belgrade in the province.
</P>
<P>
"We have a broad range options available to use," Foley said,
but refusing to speculate about what they might be.
</P>
<P>
Asked if military option is ruled out, Foley said,"I'm not
specifically addressing that option, in either a positive or
negative way."
</P>
<P>
He urged both the ethnic Albanians and Belgrade to resolve the
issue through dialogue. "Our firm message to both parties is that
the difficulties in Kosovo cannot be solved through the use of
force."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Gelbard threatened to intervene militarily in the
crisis when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Foley said there was an "erroneous report" that attributed to
Gelbard a specific comment in the regard of military option.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
