<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Jobless People Take to the Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 5 (Xinhua) -- Jobless people in more than 200
German cities, modeled on the recent mass protests by their
French counterparts, Thursday took to the streets to protest the
persisting record-high unemployment in Germany.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates of organizers, at least 50,000 people
had participated in peaceful demonstrations before banks, stock
exchanges, government institutions and offices of political
parties across the country.
</P>
<P>
In several cities, jobless demonstrators wrapped themselves in
garbage bags to present themselves as the "garbage of prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Some jobless groups from France also demonstrated in Germany
Thursday to show their solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations came as the German Labor Office released the
latest official data Thursday showing the country's unemployment
still remained at the record high of over 4.8 million, or a rate
of 12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Both the government and economists are not expecting any major
improvement on the job market within this year despite an expected
economic growth of between 2.5 percent and 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In order to put pressure on politicians, unemployed groups said
that before Germany's general elections in September, they would
launched demonstrations every month on the day when the government
released the official jobless data.
</P>
<P>
Separately, Jacques Santer, president of the European
Commission, told a conference of eastern German state premiers in
Rostock Thursday that the high levels of unemployment in Europe
could only be reduced considerably within five years provided that
international cooperation involving all social partners could be
mobilized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
